<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 27 日星期四 07:47:47 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Musk’s Fascination With the Letter X]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>该字母可以是有意义的指示符，也可以是通用的替代物。为何如此引人注目？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Ne1Dp00yo2LnFZ9W69_3H3AJrGQ=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/x_meaning_horz/original.jpg" alt="字母 X 的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br>埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 与字母<i>X</i>有着悠久的历史。它意味着什么？<br><br>首先，这是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的四个新故事：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-moralizing-reviews-social-media/674823/">道德主义正在破坏文化批评。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trump-2024-election-candidacy-criminal-appeal/674827/">2024 年大选可能会结束针对唐纳德·特朗普的案件。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/goodreads-review-bombing-amazon-moderation/674811/">好读之怒</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-girlhood-greta-gerwig/674821/">美国的少女文化真的很奇怪。</a></li><b>求解<em>X</em></b><br><br>几个月前，当我开始无意中连续阅读带有X角色的小说时，我开始对这封信感到好奇。首先，我读了理查德·福特的<i>《体育记者》</i> ，其中小说的主角在讲述他们共同的过去时称他的前妻为“X”（在该系列的下一本书中，他将她称为安）。很快，我再次发现了 X：在 Fleur Jaeggy 的<i>《纪律的甜蜜日子》</i>中，这位不知名的青少年叙述者曾一度称自己为“X 小姐”。我最近开始写凯瑟琳·莱西（Catherine Lacey）的<i>X 传记</i>，其中一位寡妇挖掘了她已故妻子的朦胧过去，她是一位艺术家，在她去世时被称为“X”。这些人物都充满了模糊性。他们是既邀请又抵制投射的人。但他们之间也没有任何关系。为什么他们有相同的名字，或者实际上没有名字？<br><br> <i>X</i>可能是一个很难确定的概念。它可以是一个有意义的指示符<i>——错误答案！</i> ——以及一个通用的替身。这封信与基督教象征主义、中学数学方程、性别中立、色情、亲吻等各种背景联系在一起。 <i>X</i>既强化了缺席感，又赋予了物体以意义。它既神圣又亵渎。截至上周末，X 也是 Twitter.com 的新名称。<br><br>埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 在成为 Twitter 所有者不到一年后， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/">将该网站的名称和徽标更改</a>为 X。他已开始删除办公室内和周围的鸟类品牌。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/24/technology/twitter-x-elon-musk.html">据报道，</a>他正在 Twitter 的自助餐厅中投影“X”，并将会议室重新命名为“eXposure”和“s3Xy”。马斯克表示，此次品牌重塑是将 Twitter 转变为一款万能应用程序的一步，就像中国应用程序微信一样。该网站的新任首席执行官琳达·亚卡里诺 (Linda Yaccarino) 在 Twitter（关于 X？）上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/lindayacc/status/1683213895463215104?s=20">发帖称</a>，“X 是无限交互的未来状态——以音频、视频、消息、支付/银行业务为中心。” （推特没有立即回应置评请求。）<br><br>字母<i>X</i>既内涵丰富又暧昧，这或许是它对马斯克的吸引力之一。 “当我看到埃隆·马斯克使用 [ <i>X</i> ] 时，我想，他绝对是一位符号学家，至少在精神上是这样，”多伦多大学符号学和语言人类学名誉教授马塞尔·达内西 (Marcel Danesi) 告诉我。 <i>X</i> “回响着各种直观的、无意识的和原型的含义，”他说。多伦多城市大学教授、 <i>《X 符号学》</i>一书的作者贾明·佩尔基 (Jamin Pelkey) 告诉我，“ <i>X</i>既是一个空洞的能指，也是一切事物的能指……你不能确定它或说它意味着<i>这个</i>，也只能意味着<i>这个</i>。”历史上有<i>X</i>标记，象征着存在和预兆：佩尔基告诉我，在西班牙的洞穴墙壁上发现了 10,000 多年前的孤立<i>X</i>标记。达内西说，在中世纪， <i>X</i>作为警告符号、十字标志以及人们密封信件的一种方式而流传。<br><br>马斯克作为 X 一代的一员，与这封信有着悠久而丰富的个人历史。 20 世纪 90 年代，他与他人共同创立了一家名为 X.com 的在线银行。当 X.com 与一家拥有 PayPal 的公司合并并且马斯克成为新实体的首席执行官时，据报道他试图逐步淘汰 PayPal 品牌并<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2023/07/25/elon-musk-paypal-twitter-x-rebrand/">用 X 取而代之</a>。当时，即 2000 年代初，马斯克认为这个名字“新颖、有趣且开放”，正如吉米·索尼在他的<i>《创始人》</i>一书中所写的那样。但 X.com <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/chafkin/status/1683475959981264900?s=46&amp;t=jVmW_mMn_l8k3nxy6JDtWg">显然让人们想起了太多色情内容</a>。很快，马斯克就被公司开除了。此后，他在自己的品牌和个人生活中都使用了<i>X</i> ：他经营着 SpaceX 公司，创建了名为 X Holdings 的法人机构和一家名为 xAI 的初创公司，并给他的一个孩子命名为 X Æ A-12。<br><br>如果<i>X</i>是马斯克的私人白鲸，那么他对这封信的兴趣也符合更广泛的品牌趋势。 <i>X</i>在千禧年之初尤其流行（想想 XBox、X Games）：“出于 20 世纪 90 年代的营销目的，X 有一定的酷感，”Stella Bugbee 本周在<i>《纽约时报》</i>上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/25/style/gen-x-elon-musk-new-logo.html">写道</a>。 “这意味着对权威的拒绝。”此后的几年里， <i>X</i>在硅谷保留了威望，谷歌的 X（以前的“Google X”，域名：x.company）使用这封信来划分其秘密的“moonshot”项目。与斯坦福大学相关的初创加速器称为 StartX。事实上，包括 Meta 和微软在内的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/technology/problem-with-x-meta-microsoft-hundreds-more-own-trademarks-new-twitter-name-2023-07-25/">数百家其他公司</a>都拥有<i>X 的</i>知识产权，这意味着马斯克和公司可能很快就会因该名称而面临诉讼。<br><br> <i>X</i>的模糊性使得这封信如此引人注目。佩尔基指出，这也是它非常适合马斯克制造麻烦、突破界限的风格的部分原因：“ <i>X</i>标记代表极端。”<br><br><b>有关的：</b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-musk-x-rebrand/674818/">为什么埃隆杀死了那只鸟</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/meta-threads-social-media-platform-death-rebirth/674638/">僵尸推特已经到来。</a></li><strong>今日新闻</strong><br><br><li>在一名法官对单独的枪支重罪指控的条款表示担忧后，亨特·拜登关于联邦税收指控的认罪协议<a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/justice-department/hunter-biden-expected-plead-guilty-criminal-tax-case-rcna96232">被搁置</a>。</li><li>南佛罗里达州顶端周围的水温已<a href="https://apnews.com/article/record-hot-water-florida-coral-climate-change-6414d44c6f120507d3ee37c059fb75cd">达到三位数</a>，可能是有史以来收集到的最热的海水测量值。</li><li>七家主要汽车制造商计划<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/26/business/energy-environment/electric-vehicles-fast-chargers-automakers.html">投资至少 10 亿美元，</a>在美国和加拿大建立电动汽车充电器网络。</li><b>更多来自<em>大西洋月刊</em></b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/authoritarianism-dictatorship-effectiveness-china/674820/">不肯消亡的独裁者神话</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/new-york-picking-up-dog-poop/674825/">什么样的恶棍不清理他们的狗？</a></li><b>文化突破</b><br><br><b>读。</b>特约撰稿人罗斯·安德森 (Ross Andersen) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/j-robert-oppenheimer-ideas-history/674814/">反思了</a>J. 罗伯特·奥本海默 (J. Robert Oppenheimer) 1949 年在<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>上发表的寻求希望的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1949/02/the-open-mind/305431/">呼吁</a>。<br><br><b>手表。</b> <i>《最厚的生存》</i> （在 Netflix 上播放）由喜剧演员米歇尔·布托 (Michelle Buteau) 主演，饰演一位心碎的造型师，在分手后与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/survival-of-the-thickest-review/674789/">屈辱和重新开始的喜悦</a>作斗争。<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">玩我们的日常填字游戏。</a><br><br><strong>聚苯乙烯</strong><br><br>要了解另一个被符号和符号包围的人的生活，我建议阅读帕特里克·拉登·基夫 (Patrick Radden Keefe) 在本周<i>《纽约客》</i>上发表的关于艺术品经销商拉里·高古轩 (Larry Gagosian) 的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2023/07/31/larry-gagosian-profile">文章</a>。这份简介记录了高古轩从在韦斯特伍德兜售海报到促成价值数千万美元交易的崛起历程。它还探讨了高古轩在加速艺术中私人利益的作用以及将美术具体化为投资类别方面所发挥的作用。基夫揭示了这个行业的一些内部阴谋，尽管该行业作为一种资产类别很突出，但在很大程度上仍然不受监管。<br><br> — 洛拉<br><br><i>Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br><em>当您使用本新闻通讯中的链接购买书籍时，我们会收到佣金。感谢您对大西洋月刊的支持</em><em>。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 23:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/elon-musk-twitter-x-letter/674836/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/elon-musk-twitter-x-letter/674836/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[UFOs Are Officially Mainstream]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>就连国会也参与其中。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/iSFnfYB__qRzlZQr4vEPE3xA4sU=/0x0:4999x2812/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1556767197_copy/original.jpg" alt="前军事情报官员大卫·格鲁施在国会作证时的黑白照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>汤姆·威廉姆斯/CQ点名/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>今天早些时候，三名证人来到国会作证，讲述他们与不明飞行物有关的经历。一位前海军飞行员讲述了他亲眼和通过雷达看到的神秘物体，以及飞行员在空中遇到它们的频率。一位退役海军指挥官描述了一次他将喷气式飞机拉到一个盘旋在海洋上空的 Tic Tac 形状的物体上，然后看着它突然加速并消失。<br><br>然而，最令人期待的言论来自一位名叫大卫·格鲁什的前军事情报官员，他上个月刚刚<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/06/alien-intact-vehicles-ufo-us-government/674323/">公开了自己的账户</a>。格鲁施告诉众议院国家安全监督小组委员会，美国政府花了几十年的时间秘密回收在地面坠毁的神秘车辆，并确定这些材料是“非人类”来源的。格鲁什表示，政府还试图对部分技术进行逆向工程。而且这一切都是秘密进行的，没有受到国会的适当监督。<br><br>在听证会上，格鲁施进一步阐述了他之前的主张，回答了议员的问题。如果民选官员以前从未听说过这项工作，那么它是如何获得资金的呢？<em>军方窃取了分配给其他项目的资金</em>。一名国防官员最近在国会作证说，美国军方尚未发现地球上存在任何外星活动的证据；这种说法正确吗？<em>这不准确。</em>是否有任何活动具有攻击性或敌意？<em>我的同事受伤了</em>。是不明飞行物，还是政府内部人员？<em>两者都有</em>。<br><br>国会半个多世纪没有举行过有关不明飞行物的听证会，最近又举行了两次听证会。从这个意义上说，我们可以将今天的事件视为历史性事件。但与其他听证会一样，这次听证会没有重大揭示，也没有对人类最关乎生存的问题——我们在宇宙中的地位——给出宏大的答案。围绕听证会的炒作——而且已经有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/technology/2023/07/congress-ufo-hearings-unidentified-aerial-phenomena-real.html">相当多的炒作</a>——更多地说明了收听节目的人，而不是格鲁施的说法。就像 20 世纪 40 年代末那样，当时华盛顿州上空的飞碟和新墨西哥州迫降的故事让全国为之着迷，今天的不明飞行物热潮表明，美国人认为他们的政府知道的比它所透露的要多。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/06/alien-intact-vehicles-ufo-us-government/674323/">阅读：为什么每个人突然都在谈论外星人</a><br><br>这种情绪并不新鲜，美国人对阴谋论的信仰也不是新鲜事。尽管<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0270429">研究表明</a>，阴谋论在当今的美国并没有变得更糟，但我们正处于公众对阴谋主义产生强烈好奇和接受的时刻。与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2020/06/qanon-nothing-can-stop-what-is-coming/610567/">QAnon</a> 、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2021/06/microchipped-vaccines-15-minute-investigation/619081/">疫苗微芯片</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/04/trump-voters-big-lie-stolen-election/629572/">被盗选举</a>相比，对不明飞行物的大规模掩盖似乎几乎是合理的——即使正如格鲁什之前在接受采访时声称的那样，这种掩盖涉及军方发现外星飞船的“死亡飞行员”。 （今天在国会，格鲁施拒绝透露有关这一点和许多其他主张的细节，称他只能向公众透露这么多，并且他可以在封闭的环境中详细阐述。）<br><br>过去几年恰逢不明飞行物文化前所未有的主流化。 2017年，当一个星际物体出现在我们的太阳系中时，大多数科学家都认为它是一颗小行星或彗星，但也有人说它可能是一艘外星飞船。 （领导后一个阵营的哈佛大学教授阿维·勒布最近<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/24/science/avi-loeb-extraterrestrial-life.html">领导了一次海​​底探险</a>，以回收他认为可能来自外星飞船的材料。）那年晚些时候， <em>《纽约时报》</em>和其他新闻媒体透露，五角大楼有一个致力于对不明飞行物进行编目的秘密计划。经过多年的明确指导后，美国宇航局决定<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2022/06/nasa-ufo-uap-research-team/661229/">权衡这个话题</a>，并<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/06/nasa-ufos-conspiracy-theories/674259/">召集一个团队</a>从“科学角度”考虑不明飞行物。谁能忘记今年军方从天上发射的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/02/unidentified-flying-objects-chinese-spy-balloon-american-alien-ufo-obsession/673068/">间谍气球</a>？<br><br>这些事件的发生与公众对地球以外宇宙的认识发生了转变，这可能有助于解释为什么人们对此感兴趣。在 20 世纪 40 年代，我们所知道的唯一行星是太阳周围的行星，而科学家最近才确定除了我们自己的星系之外还存在其他星系。如今，天文学家已经发现了 5000 多颗系外行星，望远镜几乎可以追溯到大爆炸时期。面对如此多的奇迹，我们是否与其他人分享它们的问题变得更加紧迫，甚至似乎更容易回答。 “我认为人们已经准备好，或者至少对与外星人接触的可能性感到兴奋，也许比以往任何时候都更加兴奋，”蓝色大理石太空科学研究所的天体生物学家雅各布·哈克·米斯拉告诉我。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/06/nasa-ufos-conspiracy-theories/674259/">阅读：美国宇航局了解不明飞行物的丑陋真相</a><br><br>国会也为这种主流化做出了贡献。在立法者的指示下，五角大楼去年设立了一个特别办公室，专门调查天空、海上和陆地上无法解释的现象的报告。这项努力是两党共同努力的，极右翼共和党人和进步民主党人都呼吁军方更加透明。本月，参议员查克·舒默<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/13/us/politics/ufo-records-schumer.html">提出</a>立法，将设立一个委员会，有权解密有关不明飞行物的政府文件。舒默在一份声明中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.democrats.senate.gov/newsroom/press-releases/schumer-rounds-introduce-new-legislation-to-declassify-government-records-related-to-unidentified-anomalous-phenomena-and-ufos_modeled-after-jfk-assassination-records-collection-act--as-an-amendment-to-ndaa">表示</a>：“美国公众有权了解来源不明的技术、非人类智能和无法解释的现象。”<br><br>是的，我们愿意。但<em>一些有关不明飞行物的未公开文件</em>并不等同于<em>外星人访问过地球的无可争议的证据</em>。不明飞行物就是那些我们尚无法识别的正在飞行的物体。如果军方滥用纳税人的钱来调查它不认识的神秘残骸，那就很糟糕，无论是来自其他国家的无人机还是非人类飞行器的残骸。哈克·米斯拉说：“如果情况确实如此，而且审计员没有被允许参与这些项目，并且存在非法的保密层，那么披露这一点就非常重要，与其他任何事物无关”——任何超凡脱俗的事物。但即使立法者声称不明飞行物主要是一个国家安全问题，但通过在讨论中援引外星人的说法，他们还是相信了两者之间存在联系的想法。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2022/05/congress-pentagon-ufo-hearing-aliens/629910/">阅读：UFO 讨论真正需要什么</a><br><br>格鲁施小心翼翼地告诉立法者，他只是“按照我被告知的事实说话”——也就是说，他本人没有看到任何外星人残骸或其居民的证据。总的来说，尽管他的主张充满了权威的语言，但他根本无法提供任何具体的证据。最先发表格鲁施言论的新闻网站报道称，五角大楼已批准他公开发表言论，但这仅意味着他的言论不包含机密信息，并不意味着这些言论是真实的。在国会宣誓作证也不能衡量真相。在听证会之外，一些立法者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/igorbobic/status/1684291248461426706">似乎</a>不知道如何看待这些说法。<br><br>外星入侵者的前景可能是一个国家安全问题，但它也是一个科学问题。科学需要数据，而二手资料并不是数据。 “当美国宇航局将岩石带回月球时，这些岩石会与合格的人分享，”普林斯顿大学天体物理学家、美国宇航局不明飞行物委员会主席戴维·斯佩格尔告诉我。 “想象一下，我们有一些工艺品的样本，[并且]我们真的很想了解它是什么。你可以从这些小样本中获取材料，供世界任何地方的实验室使用。”换句话说，有意义的证词将<em>展示</em>外星飞船和飞行员的证据，而不仅仅是告诉公众它们。 “那真是太棒了，”他说，但这不是我们所拥有的。今天，我们听到了一些非凡的主张，引用卡尔·萨根的话，它们需要非凡的证据。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 22:40:49 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/ufo-fever-congress-hearing-aliens/674835/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/ufo-fever-congress-hearing-aliens/674835/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Country’s Already Been Destroyed’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>以色列的政治危机是关于一种对许多人来说深刻而神圣的东西已经破裂的感觉。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/LuGeh9m3oBqWpAXEs9RFwzkS2r8=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/israel/original.jpg" alt="一名抗议者在举着以色列国旗的人群中举起火炬" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>伊利亚·叶菲莫维奇/美联社</figcaption></figure>埃兰<span class="smallcaps">·施瓦茨</span>看起来像一名战斗机飞行员。这位 40 多岁的人上周出现在以色列电视节目<em>《Ofira and Berkowitz</em> 》中——一件黑色 V 领 T 恤遮住了他修长、运动的胸部；他的黑发剪短了——以捍卫他结束空军预备役服役的决定。 “我们不是撕毁社会契约的人，”他说。 “我们发誓要为一个犹太民主国家服务。如果内塔尼亚胡要结束以色列作为自由民主国家的地位，那么违反契约的就是这个国家，而不是我们。”<br><br>节目中的另一位飞行员、以色列议会议员马坦·卡哈纳（Matan Kahana）同意施瓦茨的观点，即总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡正在将国家拖向“第三圣殿的毁灭”。不过，他坚称飞行员终止服役的决定是错误的，“因为那是审判日的武器。”他警告了后果：“拒绝服役将毁掉军队；它会撕裂这个国家。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/israel-limit-supreme-court-power-protests/674819/">纳坦·萨克斯：以色列处于边缘</a><br><br>“这个国家不是已经四分五裂了吗？”主持人之一奥菲拉·阿萨亚格 (Ofira Asayag) 进行了反击。 “这个国家已经被摧毁了。”<br><br><span class="smallcaps">在这句话中，</span>阿萨亚格准确地捕捉到了数百万以色列人的感受。以色列的政治危机不再是支持或反对内塔尼亚胡政府承诺实施的司法改革。这不再是关于法律的问题；而是关于法律的问题。这意味着数百万公民对政府的信任几乎完全被削弱。这是一种对许多人来说深刻而神圣的东西已经破碎的感觉，正如阿萨亚格所说，“这个国家已经被摧毁了”。<br><br>在节目后期，她向施瓦茨提出了他的立场所引发的棘手问题：“如果出现紧急情况，如果我们受到攻击，你是要上飞机还是不上飞机？”施瓦茨躲开了。阿萨亚格看到他蠕动，听到他的声音沙哑，盯着他的眼睛，问他一个以色列人很少问战斗机飞行员的问题：“你为什么哭？”<br><br> “我没有哭，”施瓦茨回答道。<br><br>但这并不完全正确，过了一会儿他承认。 “我在想我的祖父，”他补充道。 “他是这个国家的建设者之一……我们所有人之间有一份不成文的契约，我们都是一个人，我们在这里打仗的原因只有一个——为了在我们自己的土地上获得安全。这就是本杰明·内塔尼亚胡正在摧毁的东西。他正在带领我们摧毁第三圣殿，现在我不能再和我的祖父说话了——我必须向他解释我没有为这个国家服务？这让我内心崩溃……我的心都碎了。”<br><br><span class="smallcaps">以色列已经成为</span>一个心碎的国家，一个人民因不相信事情已经发展到这一步而瘫痪的国家。预备役军人是以色列国防军战备的重要组成部分，数千人已经退出志愿服务，这引起了一些人的嘲笑和另一些人的奉承。他们在空军中队、网络战部队、医疗队、类似于海豹突击队的特种作战部队中服役——几乎没有一支精锐部队没有受到过打击。以色列国防军参谋长赫尔齐·哈勒维和国防部长约阿夫·加兰特（内塔尼亚胡执政联盟成员）都直言不讳地指出，以色列国防军的战斗能力很可能已经受到严重削弱。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/01/benjamin-netanyahu-coalition-israel-democracy/672693/">尤西·克莱因·哈勒维：内塔尼亚胡对民主的背叛就是对以色列的背叛</a><br><br>军队能否痊愈也不清楚。如果以色列选择从约旦河西岸部分地区撤军或被迫撤军，目前占军官绝大多数且基本上反对领土妥协的宗教士兵会服从命令吗？尽管他们不同意政府的政策，但在 2005 年从加沙撤离期间他们确实服从了。但如果司法改革的反对者现在拒绝任职，其他团体有一天可能也会这样做。一个自建国以来一直处于战争状态的国家还有一支正常运作的军队吗？答案远非显而易见。<br><br>一周又一周席卷以色列街头的<span class="smallcaps">抗议运动的批评者</span>提出了两个简单的主张。首先，他们说，长期以来很明显以色列需要某种形式的司法改革。其次，他们提醒那些愿意倾听的人，这个政府是民主选举产生的。一些竞选者（但值得注意的是，不是内塔尼亚胡）直接表达了他们当选后的意图。因此，这些批评者声称，抗议活动意味着建国的特权阶层——科技企业家、飞行员、医生、教授、法官、金融工作者——在选举失败后成为痛苦的失败者。自建国以来，以色列的人口构成发生了根本性的变化。创始人的后代现在是少数，他们也不妨习惯一下。<br><br>许多抗议者承认司法改革的必要性，但坚称内塔尼亚胡的提议太过分了。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1_r-5u_lT6TIc27SjireMrlNux1roM72C/view">中间派学者</a>同意他们的观点。更不祥的是，抗议运动向所有人表明，数百万以色列人对拟议的变革感到恐惧。他们恳求说，慢点。正如备受尊敬的希伯来大学法学教授内塔·巴拉克-科伦 (Netta Barak-Corren) 所<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.asefam.org/_files/ugd/e56056_068dba527b5c4005a11440cdea743084.pdf">建议的</a>那样，让我们​​进行一次全国性对话，或者召开一次制宪会议。<br><br>但那些迫切要求立即进行深远改革的人——包括司法部长亚里夫·莱文(Yariv Levin)和议会宪法、法律和司法委员会主席西姆查·罗斯曼(Simcha Rothman)——却对此一无所获。他们告诉内塔尼亚胡，如果他犹豫，他们就会推翻他的政府。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/02/israel-palestine-west-bank-illegal-settlement-netanyahu/672944/">阅读：从这座山上，你可以看到下一次起义</a><br><br>周一，当决定性的投票在以色列议会展开时，以色列人被内塔尼亚胡夹在恳求妥协的加兰特和警告他将推翻政府的莱文之间的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/liveblog_entry/tv-report-last-minute-compromise-idea-has-collapsed/">形象</a>所吸引。老本杰明·内塔尼亚胡，这位操作大师和操纵者，已经枯萎了。他任命莱文为代理总理，而他在本周早些时候接受了一次小型心脏手术。以色列人打趣道，内塔尼亚胡已经失去了镇静剂，但莱文仍在管理政府——直接陷入深渊，利用他在议会的多数席位对所有使以色列成为经济、技术、学术、文化和军事强国的精英嗤之以鼻。他无视所有恳求他表现出克制的人，撕碎了社会契约的最后伪装。<br><br>以色列人关于如何共同生活的<span class="smallcaps">几乎每一个假设</span>现在都被撕碎了。内塔尼亚胡将极端正统派政党带入他的政府，正如他过去一直做的那样。希伯来语中的<em>正统派（Haredim）</em>是方便的联盟伙伴。他们对外交政策或大多数国内问题不感兴趣；即使坚持定居点对他们来说也不是一个主要问题。无论加入什么政府，无论是左翼、中间还是右翼，他们始终只提出两项要求：他们希望政府为他们的学校系统提供资金，他们希望继续执行以色列首任总理大卫·本·古里安发起的政策，豁免服兵役的年轻正统派男子。正统学校很少教授数学或英语，这使得毕业生完全没有准备好进入劳动力市场，并且免除年轻的正统男子服兵役以便他们可以继续在犹太教学校学习，这进一步限制了他们与世俗社会的接触。<br><br>本·古里安在以色列早年达成了这项协议，因为他认为正统派在现代犹太国家中是一种异类，是大屠杀前欧洲犹太人的残余，很快就会消亡和消失。但本-古里安完全错了。正统派现在在以色列构成了一支庞大的经济和政治力量。在本-古里安时代，每年有 400 人免服兵役，而到 2010 年，通过同样的安排免服兵役的正统派人数每年达到 62,500 人，增加了 15,000%，而以色列总人口仅增加了 1,200 人百分。<br><br>以色列前政府由纳夫塔利·贝内特领导，任期一年，亚伊尔·拉皮德任期较短，要求接受政府资助的正统学校开始教授基础的世俗研究。以色列公众仍然对哈雷迪姆不参军感到不满，但似乎因看似取得的进展而稍稍安息。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2022/09/yair-lapid-bibi-netanyahu-israel-extremism-centrism/671483/">杰弗里·戈德堡：能够结束内塔尼亚胡时代的人</a><br><br>因此，当内塔尼亚胡与极端正统政党达成联盟协议，再次免除他们的学校提供​​世俗学习，并承诺通过一项法律，永久免除他们的年轻人服兵役时，令人不满但长期存在的宽容突然破裂了。谴责拟议司法改革的抗议者高呼“平等”。每个人都明白，这不仅意味着权利平等，而且意味着义务平等。抗议者表示，他们不再为正统派付出代价并保护他们。 “他们正在吸干我们的血，”一位电视评论员<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/2023-05-21/ty-article/israeli-tv-host-under-fire-after-accusing-haredim-of-being-bloodsuckers/00000188-3dee-d7fa-a1dc-bdef92100000">说道</a>。她遭到严厉批评并被迫道歉，尽管许多人私下里对这种情绪表示赞赏。<br><br>当内塔尼亚胡试图任命以色列议会议员、正统党领袖阿耶·德里担任财政部长时，对极端正统派的愤怒更加强烈。德里在 2000 年因受贿被定罪后入狱，十年后被判逃税罪，然后作为认罪协议的一部分退出政坛。内塔尼亚胡本人是几起严重案件的被告，但他辩称，只要他还是总理，他就不会被送进监狱。他恢复德里职业生涯的计划不仅激起了首相的愤怒，首相似乎为了自己的自由而放弃了一切规范，也激起了正统派的愤怒。<br><br>巴伊兰大学法学院前院长、以色列民主研究所所长耶迪迪亚·斯特恩现任犹太民族政策研究所所长。他被广泛认为是以色列法学界的领军人物之一，并以对正统派情有独钟而闻名，他对他们的生活方式非常钦佩。但是，正如斯特恩后来告诉我的那样，三月份，当骚乱正在展开时，斯特恩去德里的家里看望了他。 “你会让成千上万的正统儿童挨饿，”斯特恩告诉他。德里看上去很困惑。 “你现在掌权了，”斯特恩解释道。 “但是左翼或中间派将会重新掌权，现在，半年，一年，甚至更长的时间。但迟早，它必然会发生。当这种情况发生时，新政府将不会关心你的孩子们有多饿，他们一天唯一的热食来自学校。选民将完全关闭政府资金的龙头，你的社区将陷入更深的贫困。”<br><br>斯特恩告诉我，德里静静地盯着他看了很长一段时间。斯特恩回忆道，很明显，德里突然明白了。<br><br>两周前，同为正统派的住房部长伊扎克·戈德克诺普夫 (Yitzhak Goldknopf) 回应了内塔尼亚胡将在其立法议程中放弃取消司法审查的传闻，这是迄今为止司法改革方案中最具争议的内容。正统派认为终止司法审查至关重要，这一步骤将阻止以色列最高法院推翻永久授予正统派男子军事豁免的法律。戈德克诺普夫告诉记者，结束司法审查是政府生存的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/haredi-minister-pm-promised-me-override-bill-imperative-for-coalition-survival/">必要条件</a>”。<br><br>戈德克诺普夫无意中所做的事情向街头数十万抗议者发出了信号，即结束司法审查是为了修复破碎的司法系统的想法只是借口。实际的议程是终止法院阻止政府向正统派投降的能力。怒火再次爆发。<br><br>然而几天后，主要的正统派报纸<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/2023-07-20/ty-article/.premium/israeli-ultra-orthodox-newspaper-calls-for-rethink-of-judicial-overhaul/00000189-72fb-de4e-adeb-ffffb4240000"><em>Yated Ne&#39;eman</em></a>似乎做出了让步。它重申了其长期以来的立场，即“民主对我们来说根本上是陌生的”，正统派在以色列的流亡程度与国家存在之前一样。不过，它表示，正统派在冲突中表明立场是不明智的。这篇社论是一个信号，表明许多正统派现在担心自己做得太过分了，并试图避免成为目前席卷以色列的愤怒的附带损害。<br><br>一些<span class="smallcaps">观察家，</span>其中包括美国犹太慈善家，顽强地坚持希望正统世界能够慢慢开放。即使在正统派内部，也有人希望正统派机构因其几十年来在以色列政治中扮演的角色而受到惩罚。<br><br> Esty Shushan 是 12 个兄弟姐妹中的长子，她自己也是四个孩子的母亲。仅此一点就使她成为正统世界中的叛逆者。她是一位诗人、电影制片人，也是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nivcharot.com/our-team">Nivcharot</a>组织的负责人，该组织致力于让正统派女性当选议会议员。<br><br>但她<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxMzc9PwyAUwPG_Bm4jlB8FDhw6G07aRBe3MwJr0VJmW239782WWHd5-STfl_ecnUObxx8dB5dTHNpdSDb20GvmC8klDLoopRKCFgWFnbZKceGoYlScFQ5eYFlyZymRjpCSYxj1Q_V0oCWg9en18vK-MmfOyS-nz-Hgm_CI17VNzcfb8avhsbZx3qf9cXgGDF__ovY2XU6w1908XyZAK0AMIGZZFjTEb9fZMc_IZRR7QAzBhAJicHk1u23yWgDCFdukNvFN9e6P1X_Gm8RW5f0ZA0ft2zz6OAGGp872ISHrUOx_AwAA__8lalvd">承认</a>，她和她的同事是一个边缘群体。掌权的拉比们对女性政治家没有兴趣，对正统女权主义者没有宽容，而且，尽管世俗文盲对年轻的正统一代来说是一场灾难，但他们没有兴趣向西方世界开放社区。确实，她承认，年轻一代甚至可以通过“犹太”手机（阻止大部分互联网）从外界获取信息，因为他们有 WhatsApp。然而，即使有了她这一代年轻时所没有的信息流，当权者的权力也没有显示出崩溃的迹象。<br><br>蜀山在最近的一次<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxMzc9PwyAUwPG_Bm4jlB8FDhw6G07aRBe3MwJr0VJmW239782WWHd5-STfl_ecnUObxx8dB5dTHNpdSDb20GvmC8klDLoopRKCFgWFnbZKceGoYlScFQ5eYFlyZymRjpCSYxj1Q_V0oCWg9en18vK-MmfOyS-nz-Hgm_CI17VNzcfb8avhsbZx3qf9cXgGDF__ovY2XU6w1908XyZAK0AMIGZZFjTEb9fZMc_IZRR7QAzBhAJicHk1u23yWgDCFdukNvFN9e6P1X_Gm8RW5f0ZA0ft2zz6OAGGp872ISHrUOx_AwAA__8lalvd">采访</a>中被问及年轻一代需要知道什么。她回答说，正统派刚刚从政府赢得的钱不会到达需要它的孩子们的手中。相反，它将交给一组经过挑选的领导者，他们对满足其羊群需求的东西同样感兴趣。<br><br>像蜀山这样的煽动者能否在正统派社区内引发新的对话？她说，现在有超过 20 名年轻女性与她一起工作，与十年前她创办该组织时相比，这是惊人的增长。但她是个女人。她是一位女权主义者。她是一名电影制片人。她在各方面都超出了正常水平，被边缘化，没有明显的途径可以做出改变。她担心，正统派世界将与以色列社会的其他部分发生冲突——尽管每个人都会从改变路线中受益。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">甚至以色列的知识产权也</span>因重塑犹太国家的愤怒海啸而动摇。阿萨夫·萨吉夫（我曾与他一起在沙勒姆中心工作）被广泛认为是以色列杰出的保守派公共知识分子。但萨吉夫已经与政府（他一再表示希望政府垮台）以及他的大多数前同事决裂。在社交媒体上，他一直在尖酸刻薄地嘲笑政府、议会成员及其支持者。<br><br>为什么？ “保守主义是一种冷静的风气，”萨吉夫在接受以色列左翼旗舰报纸<em>《国土报》</em>的长篇<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/2023-03-03/ty-article-magazine/.highlight/why-this-leading-israeli-right-wing-figure-is-praying-for-the-governments-fall/00000186-a4b3-d3d5-a7e7-aeb7a19b0000">采访</a>时说道。 “这是一场更喜欢妥协而不是争端的运动。宗教犹太复国主义曾经是一种和解、桥梁力量”，但那些日子已经过去了。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1930/10/zionism-in-palestine/306754/">摘自 1930 年 10 月号：巴勒斯坦的犹太复国主义</a><br><br>以色列右翼为何犯下如此错误？萨吉夫表示，以色列联盟核心的保守主义品牌是美国民粹主义保守主义的直接输入。但萨吉夫说，这是以色列最不需要的东西：“美国的保守主义为我们提供了窥视未来的机会，但这不是一个好兆头。共和党是一个政治、道德和文化的重灾区。”<br><br>萨吉夫对该报表示：“以色列右翼现在正在支持一项不亚于宪法政变的计划。”如果该计划付诸实施，以色列人应该期待什么？ “The dismantlement of the state&#39;s institutions … splitting the spoils between party bosses who are battling one another for power and resources, loss of public security, looting of the public coffers and deterioration into general lawlessness.”<br><br> S <span class="smallcaps">agiv&#39;s prediction</span> is now being tested. The Knesset passed the first plank of the judicial-reform package late Monday. Almost immediately, renewed protests erupted across Israel. The police, worried that people were about to scale the security fences of the heavily guarded Knesset, called in reinforcements. In Tel Aviv, thousands of protesters blocked the Ayalon, the city&#39;s main highway, shutting it in both directions for hours.<br><br> Later that night, the police had had enough. They brought in water cannons to soak the protesters, and mounted officers rode their horses directly into the crowd. Israelis went to sleep with images of violence and utter bedlam playing on their television screens.<br><br> When they awakened the following morning, many were stunned to see that several of the country&#39;s newspapers had printed <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://danielgordis.substack.com/p/the-ideological-roots-of-democracy">identical front pages</a> : Nothing but black, top to bottom, and the words “A dark day for Israeli democracy.”<br><br> Later that morning, leading news outlets <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ynet.co.il/news/article/ry8dvep9n">announced</a> that United Torah Judaism, one of the key Haredi parties, was submitting a Basic Law—a piece of legislation with constitutional status—that would declare, once and for all, that Haredi men who study Torah would be considered to have served the country. Netanyahu&#39;s Likud put a stop to the move, this time at least, but the mere mention of the proposal gave Israelis a taste of what the future was likely to hold.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2021/03/israel-election-benjamin-netanyahu/618358/">Read: &#39;Netanyahu is playing fire with the democrats&#39;</a><br><br> Every news outlet, it seemed, was trying to make sense of what had just happened. Would the opposition ask the Supreme Court to overturn the law that had been passed the previous night? It appears that it will, and most knowledgeable observers believe that there is a good chance the court will intervene. But what if the government then says that it does not recognize the court&#39;s authority?<br><br> David Barnea, the director of the Mossad, told a group of his concerned operatives what would happen if it suddenly became unclear who was in charge of the country, Israel&#39;s Channel 12 reported. “If things come to a constitutional crisis,” he assured them, “I will be on the right side”—intimating that he would side with the court against the government.<br><br> What that would look like is difficult to imagine. The security establishment against the government? The government denying the Supreme Court&#39;s authority? The tacit agreements that have held Israel together for 75 years are unraveling at an unimaginable pace.<br><br>那我们会怎样呢？ The truth is that no one knows. Which made it hard to disagree when, the morning after the Knesset vote, former Prime Minister Ehud Olmert gave voice to our worst fears. Israel, he said, “is heading into civil war.”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 16:13:42 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/-israel-netanyahu-political-crisis-supreme-court/674829/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/-israel-netanyahu-political-crisis-supreme-court/674829/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Dictator Myth That Refuses to Die]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Authoritarians would have you think that they can do certain things better than their counterparts who have to deal with checks, balances, and public opinion. Don&#39;t believe it. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/TpqHzLgeP9It6_WQ0LoQplZ_T38=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/dictators/original.jpg" alt="墨索里尼的黑白照片似乎已经解体。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>本·科特/大西洋月刊。 Sources: Getty.</figcaption></figure> Last week, at a Fox News town hall (where else?), former President Donald Trump called China&#39;s despot, Xi Jinping, a “brilliant” guy who “runs 1.4 billion people with an iron fist.” Lest anyone doubt his admiration, Trump added that Xi is “smart, brilliant, everything perfect. There&#39;s nobody in Hollywood like this guy.”<br><br> Trump is not alone. Many in the United States and around the globe see the allure of a dictator who gets things done and makes the trains run on time, no matter the rules or laws that stand in the way. According to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.voterstudygroup.org/publication/democracy-maybe">repeated polling</a> , roughly one in four Americans agrees with the statement that a “strong leader who doesn&#39;t have to bother with Congress and elections” is desirable. A much higher proportion of citizens <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2017/10/16/democracy-widely-supported-little-backing-for-rule-by-strong-leader-or-military/">agrees with that sentiment</a> elsewhere, including in some of the most populous democracies: 55 percent of Indians, 52 percent of Indonesians, 38 percent of Nigerians, and 31 percent of Japanese.<br><br> This grass-is-greener view of authoritarian rule tends to emerge most often where governments are failing to meet popular expectations. When democracy delivers, dictatorship doesn&#39;t seem like a rosy alternative. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2017/10/16/democracy-widely-supported-little-backing-for-rule-by-strong-leader-or-military/">Only 6 percent</a> of Germans and 9 percent of Swedes are seduced by strongmen.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/democracy-hold-customer-service-airline-insurance-junk-fees/673201/">Brian Klaas: Democracy has a customer-service problem</a><br><br> Admiration for autocracy is built on a pernicious lie that I call the “myth of benevolent dictatorship.” The myth is built on three flimsy pillars: first, that dictators produce stronger economic growth than their democratic counterparts; second, that dictators, unswayed by volatile public opinion, are strategic long-term thinkers; and third, that dictators bring stability, whereas divided democracies produce chaos.<br><br> Two decades ago, the United States and its Western allies became embroiled in Iraq and later blundered into the financial crisis, leading think tanks to begin <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fpc.org.uk/publications/the-beijing-consensus/">praising the “Beijing Consensus,”</a> or the “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/china/archive/2013/03/why-the-china-model-isnt-going-away/274237/">China Model</a> ,” as an alternative to liberal democracy. Critiques of democracy surged in popularity in the era of Trump and Brexit. In the United States, intellectual publications ran articles arguing that the problem was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2016/04/america-tyranny-donald-trump.html">too much democracy</a> . In 2018, <em>The Times</em> of London published a column titled “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/our-timid-leaders-can-learn-from-strongmen-3xhqhk0zw">Our Timid Leaders Can Learn From Strongmen</a> .” China&#39;s state media, capitalizing on the West&#39;s democratic woes, argued that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/03/14/china-paper-says-rise-of-racist-trump-shows-democracy-is-scary/">democracy is a “scary” system</a> that produces self-inflicted wounds.<br><br> But events and new research in the past several years have taken a wrecking ball to the long-standing myth of benevolent dictatorship. All three pillars of the lie are crumbling. Every fresh data point <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://winstonchurchill.org/resources/quotes/the-worst-form-of-government/">proves Winston Churchill right</a> : “Democracy is the worst form of Government, except for all those other forms that have been tried from time to time.”<br><br> Let&#39;s start with the myth that dictatorships produce stronger growth. This falsehood arose from a few well-known, cherry-picked examples, in which despots oversaw astonishing transformations of their national economy. Starting in the late 1950s, Lee Kuan Yew helped transform Singapore from a poor, opium-filled backwater into a wealthy economic powerhouse. And in China, per capita GDP rose from nearly $318 in 1990 to more than $12,500 today. Those successes are eye-popping.<br><br> But a systematic evaluation of the overall data reveals another reality. Even with these outliers of strong growth, most rigorous studies have found <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://dpsa.dk/papers/Nyrup_DPSA.pdf#cite.0@bjornskov2018regime">limited or no evidence</a> that authoritarian regimes produce better economic growth than democratic ones. Some researchers, such as the political economists Darren Acemoglu and James Robinson, have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/205014/why-nations-fail-by-daron-acemoglu-and-james-a-robinson/">found compelling evidence</a> that the inclusive political institutions of democracy are one of the strongest factors in producing stable, long-term growth.<br><br> When authoritarian regimes do succeed economically, they often do so at a cost, because even booming dictatorships are prone to catastrophic busts. As the political scientist Jacob Nyrup has written: “China has within a 50-year time frame both experienced a famine, where 20-45 million people died, and an economic boom, where hundreds of millions of people were lifted out of poverty.” The rosiest interpretation of the authoritarian economic data, then, is that autocrats may sometimes preside over marginally higher growth, but with a much greater risk of economic collapse. That&#39;s not a wise trade-off.<br><br> However, the myth of strongmen as economic gurus has an even bigger problem. Dictators turn out to have manipulated their economic data for decades. For a long time, they&#39;ve fooled us. But now we have proof: The reason their numbers sometimes seem too good to be true is that they are.<br><br> Every government has motivation to fudge its economic data. But democracies have institutions that provide oversight and block politicians from that impulse, ensuring accurate figures. No such checks exist in dictatorships.<br><br> That difference led Luis Martinez, an economist at the University of Chicago, to test whether despots were <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thedocs.worldbank.org/en/doc/350051528721174623-0050022018/original/Nightlights.pdf">overstating their growth rate</a> . He did so with an ingenious method. Previous studies have verified the presence of a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev-economics-080217-053355">strong, accurate correlation</a> between the amount of nighttime light captured by satellites and overall economic activity. When economies grow, they emit more nighttime light (which is why you can clearly pick out cities on <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://earth.google.com/web/@37.49351744,-84.10377216,1070.56549039a,7585747.77774096d,35y,0h,0t,0r/data=CisSKRIgMGY3ZTJkYzdlOGExMTFlNjk5MGQ2ZjgxOGQ2OWE2ZTciBWVhcnRo">a nighttime satellite image</a> , and why the density of light is so much lower in Africa than, say, in Europe or on the American East Coast). High-resolution images allow researchers to track changes in nighttime illumination over time, and the detailed, granular data these images produce are nearly impossible to manipulate. Martinez discovered an astonishing disparity suggesting that dictators have been <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://harris.uchicago.edu/news-events/news/qa-luis-martinez-exposes-way-dictators-exaggerate-economic-performance">overstating their GDP growth</a> by about 35 percent.<br><br> And the more the numbers are checked, the more manipulation is exposed. In Rwanda, where <em>The New York Times</em> has named President Paul Kagame <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/08/magazine/paul-kagame-rwanda.html">“the global elite&#39;s favorite strongman”</a> because of his apparently brilliant record of economic growth, the government claimed that it had decreased poverty by 6 percent from 2010 to 2014. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://roape.net/2017/07/26/faking-rwandan-gdp-growth-myth/">Researchers found</a> that the inverse was true: Poverty had actually surged by 5 to 7 percent. Fittingly, the notion that Benito Mussolini <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-11-15/stop-saying-mussolini-made-the-trains-run-on-time">made the trains run on time was a lie</a> ; he built ornate stations and invested in train lines used by elites, but the commuting masses got left behind.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2021/01/xi-jinping-china-economy-jack-ma/617552/">Read: The undoing of China&#39;s economic miracle</a><br><br> Even China, the apparent authoritarian economic miracle, is showing <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://foreignpolicy.com/2023/07/18/china-economy-gdp-decline-deflation-real-estate-zero-covid/">signs of slowing down</a> , its growth model <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/china-economy-outlook-growth-model-globalization-exports-middle-income-trap-2023-7?r=US&amp;IR=T">no longer so well matched</a> to the global economy. Such cracks in growth are an innate feature of autocracy. Because dictatorships criminalize dissent, normal mechanisms of economic feedback are broken, and the system doesn&#39;t self-correct when blundering into economic mistakes. Beijing&#39;s quixotic quest to maintain perpetual “zero COVID” was a case in point. Autocrats are adept at building ports and roads and mines. But thriving modern economies are sustained less by open mines than by open minds, of which dictatorships, by design, have a limited supply.<br><br> Advocates for the myth of benevolent dictatorship conveniently ignore a crucial fact, which is that much of the growth in autocracies comes either from manufacturing products that were invented in the more open societies of the democratic West, or from exporting goods to rich democracies. (The <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://oec.world/en/profile/country/chn">top destinations</a> for Chinese exports are the United States, Japan, and South Korea.) In that way, even the outliers of autocratic growth depend for their success on the innovation and consumer wealth of democracies. Would China have lifted millions out of poverty through export-led growth quite so fast if democratic America hadn&#39;t become an economic powerhouse first?<br><br> The myth&#39;s second pillar turns out to be no less rickety than the first. It holds that dictators are more strategic long-term thinkers than democrats because they&#39;re not beholden to fickle public opinion. But this lie is believable only if you don&#39;t understand how most dictatorships actually work.<br><br> Over more than a decade, I&#39;ve <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bookshop.org/p/books/corruptible-who-gets-power-and-how-it-changes-us-brian-klaas/16255009?ean=9781982154103">studied and interviewed despots</a> and the henchmen who surround them. One conclusion I&#39;ve drawn is that making decisions based on bad information is an intrinsic feature of the systems dictators run. The longer despots cling to power, the more likely they are to fall into what I call “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/03/putin-dictator-trap-russia-ukraine/627064/">the dictator trap</a> ,” in which they crush dissent, purge anyone who challenges them, and construct their own reality through propaganda, all to maintain control. Speaking truth to power in such a system can literally be deadly. As a result, dictators are told only what they want to hear, not what is true, and they begin to believe their own lies. Vladimir Putin&#39;s catastrophic war in Ukraine is a tragic illustration of the dictator trap: Putin got high on his own supply, and innocent Ukrainians are the victims of his power trip.<br><br> Despots often use their power not for long-term planning, but for short-term self-glorification, as no end of examples can attest. Turkmenistan&#39;s former dictator Saparmurat Niyazov blew millions to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11095257">build, in his own honor, a golden statue</a> that would rotate to always face the sun. In another stroke of genius, he <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/4307583.stm">closed all rural hospitals</a> so that the sick could have the privilege of being treated in his pristine marble capital of Ashgabat. Most of the population lived outside the city, and countless thousands likely died because they couldn&#39;t reach a hospital in time. His successor erected an <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-54894828">enormous golden statue</a> of his favorite breed of dog. Thankfully, democracies have checks and balances to suppress such narcissistic whims.<br><br> The most persistent pillar of the myth, however, is the one that holds that dictators produce stability. Some dictators have hung on to power for decades. Before his death, Muammar Qaddafi ruled Libya for 42 years. Paul Biya of Cameroon, an 89-year-old despot <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.the-star.co.ke/news/africa/2023-01-23-africas-oldest-president-forgets-where-he-is-while-addressing-global-summit/">who had no idea where he was</a> during a recent event, took office during the Vietnam War. Putin has been in power for more than two decades; Xi has ruled for only one so far, but he appears prepared to retain his position indefinitely.<br><br> To stay in power, authoritarian leaders face constant trade-offs. If they strengthen military or paramilitary leaders, they face the risk of a coup d&#39;état. But if they weaken their men under arms, then they can&#39;t protect themselves from external invasion. To keep their elites happy, despots need to make them rich through corruption—usually at the expense of the population. But a ruling class awash in ill-gotten gains could inspire a revolution, or a wild card: assassination. Autocrats appear stable, but they&#39;re not. They&#39;re constantly vulnerable, forced to make every decision based on what will stave off threats to survive in power.<br><br> The stability that does exist in autocracies is, ironically, derived partially from the trappings of democracy. Recent research has made clear that dictators have developed mechanisms to “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ciaotest.cc.columbia.edu/journals/twq/v37i4/f_0033652_27429.pdf">mimic democracy to prolong autocracy</a> .” Most authoritarian leaders now <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://yalebooks.yale.edu/book/9780300246650/how-to-rig-an-election/">hold elections, but rig them</a> . Some use parliaments or courts to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/rule-by-law/64D05AB3BEAFEE4C86E01883B9A143DC">enact unpopular decisions</a> while avoiding blame.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/12/the-autocrats-are-winning/620526/">From the December 2021 issue: The bad guys are winning</a><br><br> Eventually, though, dictatorships tend to fall apart. And when they collapse, they <em>really</em> collapse. Elections in democracies change governments, not regimes. Personalist dictatorships, by contrast, often implode. When Qaddafi was killed, Libya disintegrated. He had deliberately designed the political system to function only with him at its center. The same could be true of Putin&#39;s Russia. When he is toppled or dies, the country won&#39;t have a smooth, peaceful transition.<br><br> The often-disastrous demise of autocrats creates a negative feedback loop. Nearly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vanderbilt.edu/csdi/events/Geddes927.pdf">seven in 10 leaders of personalist dictatorships</a> end up jailed, exiled, or killed once they lose power. While in power, many despots are aware of this grim fact, and so they use violence to stay in power, often growing more extreme as they lurch toward their downfall. The effect can hardly be called “stability,” even if the same person occupies the palace for decades.<br><br> For anyone who still clings to the illusion that dictatorships are likely to be prosperous, strategically wise, or internally stable, I propose a simple test. Imagine that someone wrote down the names of all the countries in the world on little slips of paper and then separated them into two hats: one for democracy, one for dictatorships. You would select one of the two hats, draw a slip of paper from it, look at the name, and then spend the rest of your life living in that country. Who knows, maybe you&#39;d get lucky and end up in an authoritarian regime that seems stable and is producing steady growth. But I know which hat I would choose. And even if you fantasize about finding the unicorn that is a benevolent strongman, I suspect you do too.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/authoritarianism-dictatorship-effectiveness-china/674820/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/authoritarianism-dictatorship-effectiveness-china/674820/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The 2024 Election Could Be the End of the Cases Against Donald Trump]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>全国最有权势的办公室为他提供了终止针对他的案件的最佳机会。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/c1zeQnPhyPUyfW_SccJ8rdMC4tQ=/0x0:3514x1977/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1439325943-1/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普戴着“让美国再次伟大”帽子的照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> McNamee / Getty</figcaption></figure>如果唐纳德·特朗普（看起来很可能）成为明年的共和党总统候选人，那么 2024 年的选举将是对几个关键问题的公投：美国威权主义的前景、充满活力的民主的延续、行政部门与政府之间的关系。其他两个政府部门，以及其他许多具有重大意义的部门。<br><br>这也将是一次关于特朗普是否会对其行为承担法律责任的公投。特朗普面临多起民事诉讼和至少两起刑事起诉（还有两起似乎即将到来）。如果特朗普赢得连任，几乎可以肯定这些问题都不会得到解决——至少不会以不利于他利益的方式得到解决，任何合理的制度都会承认这种可能性。这就是总统的权力。<br><br>首先来看最简单的案件：他因违反与保留机密文件有关的《间谍法》而在佛罗里达州等待起诉，以及他预计因与 1 月 6 日叛乱有关的行动而受到起诉。如果特朗普当选，这些案件都不会导致对特朗普有罪的最终判决（更不用说监禁）。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trump-second-term-isolationist-fascism/674791/">克里斯托弗·布朗宁：一种新型法西斯主义</a><br><br>海湖庄园文件案定于 2024 年 5 月开庭审理。尽管许多人怀疑这一审理日期会推迟（并非没有根据），但让我们姑且考虑一下审判如期进行且在 6 月某个时间进行的可能性或者 2024 年 7 月，陪审团判定特朗普有罪。毫无疑问，特朗普会对这样的判决提出上诉，同样几乎毫无疑问，主审法官艾琳·坎农(Aileen Cannon)将允许他在上诉中保持自由。<br><br>在我的职业生涯中，我处理过多起刑事上诉。即使是最简单的情况，在不到一年的时间内也没有得到解决。这就是我们上诉系统的运作方式；诉讼程序根本没有紧迫感（需要明确的是，在正常的业务过程中也不应该有紧迫感——审判已经结束，记录完整；对这些诉讼程序进行成熟和深思熟虑的审查需要时间）。结果是，特朗普对其联邦定罪的上诉（假设一项得到保证）很可能仍在第十一巡回法院悬而未决，该法院对佛罗里达州的联邦审判拥有上诉管辖权，至少到 2025 年中期——远远超过了选举和进入下一个总统任期。即使上诉能够很快结束，特朗普也不可避免地会向最高法院申请复审，这需要更多的时间。<br><br>类似的日历将适用于可能很快由华盛顿特区的特别检察官提出的 1 月 6 日相关指控，即使该审判比佛罗里达州的审判更快进行（例如，在 3 月或 4 月）明年（这是一个很大的假设，因为联邦法院必须就一项有效的审判进行谈判，并且与原定于 3 月在纽约举行的审判不冲突），向对案件拥有管辖权的华盛顿特区巡回法院提出上诉的机会从首都联邦法院到最高法院，不到 10 个月的时间几乎为零。<br><br>简而言之，在我看来，针对特朗普的任何联邦指控都不可能在 2025 年 1 月 20 日之前最终确定——根本不可能。同样可以肯定的是，特朗普任命的总检察长（无论是谁）的首要行动之一就是司法部采取行动，驳回针对总统的案件，无论案件处于悬而未决的阶段。简而言之，如果特朗普在 2024 年 11 月赢得连任，针对他的联邦案件很可能会在他就职后 24 小时内终止，而没有最终解决方案。这并不意味着这些程序毫无价值。如果特朗普在任何一次审判中被定罪，美国将受益于确定其犯罪行为的历史记录。但当我们再忍受他四年的统治，并且他继续避免任何表面上的实际责任时，这并不能让人感到安慰。<br><br>当我们转向特朗普在纽约已悬而未决的案件以及预计不久将在佐治亚州审理的另一起案件中面临的州指控时，情况变得更加复杂。根据定义（至少就宪法而言），这些州是独立的主权国家，特朗普领导下的联邦政府不能指示驳回那些针对他的案件，特朗普也不能赦免自己在州的罪行，因为他的赦免权是同样，仅限于联邦事务。因此，这些案件将会继续进行。<br><br>但天哪，他们很难得到解决。<br><br>首先，我们可以相信特朗普领导的司法部认为，现任总统至少在任职期间不受州起诉。他们的主张也有一定的道理。毕竟，如果纽约和佐治亚州地方检察官可以在特朗普任职期间对他进行审判，那么任何反对总统的州的民选官员都可能利用其权力对总统提出当地刑事指控。如何阻止一位民选共和党检察官在一个非常红色的州对乔·拜登总统提出虚假指控？<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/trump-hunter-biden-indictment-plea-deal/674543/">凯特·肖：反应揭示了特朗普与拜登的一切</a><br><br>风险超出了假设。我们已经看到当选的总检察长如何以更加政治化的方式使用他们的权力。从“合理”起诉到“不公正”起诉的飞跃主要取决于旁观者的看法。这就是为什么50多年前，水门事件特别检察官办公室在这一点上实际上站在总统一边，声称“出于联邦制的考虑，将禁止在州法院起诉他”。宪法文本中没有任何内容禁止国家起诉行政长官，但也没有授权这样做，因此这个问题从未得到明确解决。但如果特朗普当选，我们可以肯定，最高法院会做出什么决定，谁也说不准。<br><br>这也不是州检察官需要克服的唯一法律障碍。特朗普要求将纽约起诉移交给联邦法院的努力迄今已被拒绝， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.foxnews.com/politics/judge-us-cant-replace-trump-e-jean-carroll-slander-suit">联邦政府在一些针对他的民事诉讼中取代特朗普的努力也被</a>拒绝。然而，如果特朗普重返办公室，这些论点将具有更大的影响力。他作为联邦官员的身份以及他个人对民事诉讼的责任所造成的对政府活动的干扰将变得更加明显。特朗普任命的总检察长几乎肯定会在法庭上尽最大努力向他们施压。<br><br>其他挑战可能不那么合法，但本质上更实际。如果纽约和佐治亚州坚持他们的立场，特朗普报复的性质将仅受他的想象力的限制。例如，如果他试图从这两个州撤回联邦执法资金，会发生什么？如果他指示联邦调查局退出合作调查工作怎么办？如果在共和党领导的佐治亚州，他向州立法机构施压，要求其通过法律限制亚特兰大地方检察官的权力或要求她驳回此案，结果会怎样？国家不应该回答这些问题。<br><br>如果特朗普再次当选，他几乎肯定会避免对其犯罪行为承担责任，这只是他对法治构成的更广泛威胁的一小部分。但这是一种具有象征意义的可能性，散发着王权的气息。可悲的是，现实是显而易见的：当美国人在 2024 年参加投票时，如果特朗普是候选人，他们将不会简单地在两种政治选择之间进行选择；他们会做出选择。他们也将做出该国历史上最重要的选择之一。他们将在“没有人凌驾于法律之上”的现代信念和回到政治领导人可以不受惩罚的时代之间做出选择。我们自己的民族性格取决于我们做出的选择。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 12:18:49 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trump-2024-election-candidacy-criminal-appeal/674827/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trump-2024-election-candidacy-criminal-appeal/674827/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Wrath of Goodreads]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>作者受到那些懒得阅读他们作品的人的摆布。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/DcJB2yRT39HblID42TYJ8YY2-uc=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/goodreads_final_3/original.jpg" alt="穿过书本的箭头" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Ben Kothe / The Atlantic.资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure> <small><i data-stringify-type="italic">This article was featured in One Story to Read Today, a newsletter in which our editors recommend a single must-read from</i> The Atlantic <i data-stringify-type="italic">, Monday through Friday.</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Sign up for it here.</a></i></small><br><br>当梅根·诺兰出版她的第一部小说时，其他作家用“不祥的语气”警告她有关 Goodreads 网站的问题。这位年轻的爱尔兰作家在 2020 年冬天查看了这本书的列表，那天第一本校样到达了她家。 “除了我和出版商之外，没有人见过它，”她最近<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newstatesman.com/culture/books/2023/07/goodreads-book-reviews-degrading-literary-culture">写道</a>。 “尽管如此，它已经收到了一条评论：两颗星，是由一个与我有无关紧要的个人不和的人留下的。他根本不可能读过这本书。”<br><br> Goodreads的可怕威力在出版界是公开的秘密。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2013/04/the-simple-reason-why-goodreads-is-so-valuable-to-amazon/274548/">亚马逊于 2013 年收购的</a>评论网站可以塑造围绕一本书或一位作者的积极和消极的对话。 Today&#39;s ostensible word-of-mouth hits are more usually created online, either via Goodreads or social networks such as Instagram and TikTok.<br><br>出版商知道这些动态的重要性，因此他们不仅向可能库存图书的独立书商，而且还向可能制作相关内容的影响者发送高级阅读副本（ARC）。 “有一种假设是，如果你收到 ARC，你就会发布有关它的信息，”文学播客<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thestackspodcast.com/about/"><em>The Stacks</em></a>的主持人 Traci Thomas 告诉我，“无论是在你的 Goodreads 上，在你的 Instagram 上，在你的 TikTok 上，告诉其他人在你的书店，或者其他什么地方。所以这就是为什么一本尚未出版的书有这么多评论的结果。”<br><br>许多图书博主都认真地在自己的帖子中添加免责声明，感谢出版商为他们提供 ARC“以换取诚实的评论”。但公开免费赠品远不是合同要求，甚至不是社会规范。因此，你无法轻易辨别哪些早期评论家真正读过这本书，哪些评论家可能会对社交媒体的讨论做出反应（或者，正如诺兰在她的案例中所怀疑的那样，是在诉诸个人恩怨）。<br><br>这很重要，因为病毒式营销活动始终针对未出版的书籍。通常会发生的情况是，Instagram 或 TikTok 上的一个有影响力的声音认为一本书“有问题”，然后该人的数十名粉丝前往 Goodreads，让作者的冒犯更加广为人知。回应这些攻击的作者可能会让情况变得更糟。凯瑟琳·黑尔（Kathleen Hale）对一位刻薄的评论者感到非常愤怒，以至于她找到了这位女士的地址，她后来<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/oct/18/am-i-being-catfished-an-author-confronts-her-number-one-online-critic">写道</a>，该网站警告她不要订婚：“在页面底部，Goodreads 发布了以下指令（如果您已登录）作为一名作者，它出现在你写的每本书的差评之后）：“我们真的，真的（真的！）认为你不应该对此评论发表评论，甚至不应该感谢审稿人。”大多数作者我知道阅读他们的 Goodreads 评论，然后独自默默地对他们感到愤怒。因为我是个怪人，所以我从自己身上获得了巨大的乐趣——抱怨越琐碎、莫名其妙越好。 “我听了有声读物，到了第三章，她在‘男性’这个词之前的停顿开始让我恼火，”我的书《<em>难相处的女人》</em>的一篇评论中写道。<br><br>当投诉越来越多、越来越严重时，就被称为“评论轰炸”或“结队”。 Goodreads 闪电战可能会破坏整个出版计划，吓坏计划讨论发行的商业读书俱乐部，甚至促使紧张的出版商削减有争议书籍的营销预算。上个月，《<em>美食、祈祷、爱情》</em>的作者伊丽莎白·吉尔伯特 (Elizabeth Gilbert) 撤回了她即将出版的小说<em>《雪林》(The Snow Forest)</em> ，原因是她透露小说以苏联为背景后遭到强烈反对。 <em>《雪森林》</em>的 Goodreads 页面指责她将俄罗斯灵魂浪漫化，该页面现已被删除。 “我会为你裁掉这份工作——他们没有，”一位评论者写道。另一位写道：“就像她在<em>这部</em>小说中的角色不知道二战事件一样，伊丽莎白·吉尔伯特本人似乎也不知道俄罗斯现在正在对乌克兰进行种族灭绝战争，因为我确信她是否知道，她会意识到这本书是多么的聋子。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/06/elizabeth-gilbert-book-release-postponed-ukraine-war/674379/">阅读：吃饭、祈祷、迎合</a><br><br>这本书原定于明年二月出版，但在一段视频中宣布“现在不是出版这本书的时候”，吉尔伯特基本上赞同 Goodreads 的批评：“我不想给一群那些已经经历过并且正在继续遭受严重和极端伤害的人。”<br><br>现在，我不知道<em>《雪林》</em>是否让俄罗斯人的灵魂变得浪漫，或者是否会对乌克兰人造成“伤害”。和我的同事富兰克林·福尔一样，我<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/06/elizabeth-gilbert-book-release-postponed-ukraine-war/674379/">发现这些指控令人难以置信</a>。但显而易见的事实是，我们都不知道，因为——这应该是显而易见的，尽管最近的事件表明事实并非如此<em>——你不知道一本你没有读过的书里有什么</em>。你也不知道你没有看过的电影、你没有听过的专辑、或者你没有点击过的文章中有什么。这曾经很重要。现在不再这样了，因为我们生活在一个你可以通过传播头条新闻的屏幕截图和断章取义的视频剪辑来获得点赞的世界，而且营销活动规模足够大，它们本身就构成了艺术陈述。 （<em>芭比</em>，我在看着你。）<br><br>不幸的是，在这种病毒般的地狱景观中最有可能遇到麻烦的艺术作品是那些探索复杂的、煽动性主题的艺术作品，例如性、种族和身份。 Goodreads 的另一部电视剧<em>《一切都很好》</em>最近播出，这是塞西莉亚·拉贝斯 (Cecilia Rabess) 撰写的处女作，于 6 月 6 日出版。该剧的情节围绕一位年轻、进步的黑人女性，在唐纳德·特朗普 (Donald Trump) 上台前爱上了一位保守的白人。选举。拉贝斯告诉我，“它显然解决了美国有关种族、阶级、政治和身份的一些避雷针问题”，因此她预计 Goodreads 和类似网站会引起强烈反响。 “但我认为人们肯定没有读过这本书。所以我不知道他们是如何得出这样的结论的——这本书没有仔细、深思熟虑或有意地处理这些主题。”<br><br>将这种描述视为作家的轻描淡写。 “如果你用它来为种族主义者开脱，那它就不是恋人的敌人，”一篇典型的一星评论<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:NBNOok5wJxMJ:https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/62919844&amp;cd=6&amp;hl=en&amp;ct=clnk&amp;gl=uk">写道</a>，引用了一个常见的浪漫小说比喻。 “有些作者不应该成为作者，这是什么鬼！？”另一个提供了。 “我还没有读过这本书，也不打算读，但读过概要后，我将其评为一星，”第三位承认。<br><br>就<em>《一切都很好》</em>而言，这种批评似乎是从 TikTok 开始的，一些著名的创作者批评了这本书。随后，愤怒的情绪蔓延到 Goodreads，那些创作者的粉丝可以在那里表达他们的不满。 “我没有也不会读这篇文章，我来自抖音，我希望销量如此糟糕，以至于书店不得不扔掉所有库存，因为它拒绝出售。任何获得 ARC 的人都应该感到羞耻，”另一条一星评论指出。<br><br>对于拉贝斯来说，这段经历是残酷的。 “作为一名艺术家，你要做好人们不会与你的作品产生共鸣的心理准备，”她说。 “但我认为，当人们认为你自己有问题，或者你自己造成伤害，或者他们用任何语言来描述它时，感觉会有所不同。感觉有点超现实。”这种强烈的反对可能在 Goodreads 上很盛行，但很快就蔓延到了更广泛的互联网上。拉贝斯是黑人，她收到了愤怒的直接信息和电子邮件，以及她发布的任何社交媒体帖子下的辱骂性评论。 “他们说我和我的孩子们的坏话。叫我<em>浣熊</em>，还有其他令人不快的辱骂。告诉我，我还不如死了好。”<br><br>愤怒是四散的。使用种族诽谤的评论者显然知道拉贝斯的种族，但她想知道其他一些在线评论家是否认为她是一名白人作家，侵犯了他们认为应该为有色人种作家保留的领域。虽然作者被明智地告知不要阅读评论——当然也不要与批评者打交道——但当批评者直接出现在你的（虚拟）面前并向你大喊他们的观点时，这就更难了。<br><br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/164999338-the-snow-forest">阅读：正在扼杀创造力的公司</a><br><br>碰巧的是，播客特雷西·托马斯 (Traci Thomas) 也是不喜欢拉贝斯这本书的人之一——尽管是在一月份读过预印本之后。 “这是一本令人讨厌的书，”她告诉我。她反对她所认为的故事的寓意：爱征服一切，即使是特朗普的支持者。 “书中的男朋友乔什戴着一顶让美国再次伟大的帽子，就像对[女主角]说种族主义的废话。她说，<em>没关系</em>。对她来说最大的启示是她仍然可以选择爱他。我就想：好吧，酷，走吧——我要把这本书撕成碎片。”<br><br>最终，托马斯总结道：“我不知道这本书是否需要存在。”<br><br>托马斯告诉我，尽管她自己有强烈的感受，但她有时会因为自己的评论被下意识的反应和“表演性盟友”包围而感到不安，甚至是那些与她有共同政治观点的人。 “有些人刚开始从事反种族主义工作，或者支持 LGBTQ 人群，或者从事残疾人活动等等。他们觉得他们的工作就是在不了解更大历史背景的情况下指出他们注意到的事情。”为了说明这一点，她举了一个例子：想象一位作者写了一本关于黑人儿童骑三轮车的书，“然后我会看到这样的评论，‘这本书没有谈论骑自行车的黑人学龄前儿童，他们“也面临风险。”<br><br>这种动态解释了病毒式传播最开始违反直觉的一个方面：许多人似乎都针对那些在 99% 的政治观点上与批评者意见一致的作者。一种奇怪的进步性的人为优势在这里发挥作用：任何人都可以谴责安·库尔特的最新书，但指出女权主义或反种族主义书籍或黑人女性作家的小说中的缺陷，将批评家确立为占有者更高的道德层面。<br><br>这样做的最终结果是阻碍了吉尔伯特等进步作家和拉贝斯等有色人种作家的书籍。后者对<em>《一切都好》</em>的争议持哲学态度，将这种强烈反对视为她在小说中探索的政治时刻的代表——“人们感到缺乏社区和联系，只是想要一种联系的方式，一种表达的方式”或表达自己的愤怒。”<br><br>当然，如果 Goodreads 愿意，它可以在一夜之间解决评论轰炸问题。当依赖于用户生成内容的服务仅受到轻微审核时，这始终是一个有意识的决定，而且通常是冷酷的商业决定。吉尔伯特下架了她的小说后， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2023/07/01/amazon-goodreads-elizabeth-gilbert/"><em>《华盛顿邮报》</em></a>观察到，据报道为 Goodreads 支付 1.5 亿美元的亚马逊现在对维护或更新该网站兴趣不大。对流量大的网站进行重大改变可能代价高昂，并且有可能惹恼现有用户群： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-06-21/reddit-blackout-previews-social-media-s-future-in-the-ai-era">Reddit</a>最近面临着版主对开发人员访问其工具方式的抗议，以及埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 在 Twitter（或者无论它现在被称为什么）的任期。有一天，我将在商学院教授一张标题为“如何失去广告商并疏远人们”的幻灯片。清除重复帐户可能会扫除一些狂热的 Goodreads 用户（他们无法忍受只分享一次自己的观点），并使该网站感觉不那么忙碌和令人兴奋。<br><br> Goodreads 发言人 Suzanne Skyvara 通过电子邮件告诉我，该网站“非常重视维护评级的真实性和完整性，并保护我们的读者和作者社区。”她补充说，Goodreads 正在努力“领先于违反我们的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/guidelines">评论</a>或<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.goodreads.com/community/guidelines">社区</a>准则的内容和帐户”，并“增加了会员向我们举报内容的方式。”<br><br>亚马逊主要网站采取了多项措施来阻止评论轰炸：来自经过验证的书籍购买者的评论被标记为这样，以增强其可信度，而星级评级是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wired.com/story/amazon-stars-ratings-calculated/">复杂算法</a>的产物，而不是简单地对所有评论进行平均。分数。 Goodreads 可以采取更严格的措施，但是，为了提高质量而减少数量并不符合公司的利益，因为它的全部吸引力都是基于草根的声音。 “Goodreads 确实需要一种机制来阻止对作家的一星攻击，”作家罗克珊·盖伊 (Roxane Gay) 在吉尔伯特六月份发表声明后<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/rgay/status/1668336078447869952?s=20">发推文说</a>。 “这削弱了他们仅存的一点信誉。”特蕾西·托马斯表示同意。她在一封电子邮件中告诉我，她希望看到“经过验证的用户或评论获得支票（或其他东西），以换取证明他们已经读过这本书。”<br><br>如果亚马逊不会投入资源来控制 Goodreads 的愤怒，那么这里的公平需要的是一个强烈的禁忌：<em>不要评论你没有读过的书</em>。我们应该像污蔑在公共交通工具上剪指甲、满嘴说话或声称你的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-42880690">孔雀</a>是服务性动物一样污蔑无知的观点。我们其他人的一点自控力将使作家更容易处理煽动性的话题，因为他们知道他们只会因为他们实际做过的事情而受到批评。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 12:15:22 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/goodreads-review-bombing-amazon-moderation/674811/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/goodreads-review-bombing-amazon-moderation/674811/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Moralism Is Ruining Cultural Criticism]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The left has embraced an approach long favored by the evangelical right. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1CriJUMaNciOGkNSpMn36lYdM60=/0x0:3600x2025/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/OPR_Tsr1Sht4_RGB_2_copy/original.jpg" alt="原子弹云与男人剪影" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>环球影业</figcaption></figure>When I was growing up in a conservative evangelical community, one of the top priorities was to manage children&#39;s consumption of art. The effort was based on a fairly straightforward aesthetic theory: Every artwork has a clear message, and consuming messages that conflict with Christianity will harm one&#39;s faith. Helpfully, there was a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L9CeHJXasrk">song</a> whose lyrics consisted precisely of this aesthetic theory: “Input Output.”<br><br><p> Input, output,<br> What goes in is what comes out.<br> Input, output,<br> That is what it&#39;s all about.<br> Input, output,<br> Your mind is a computer whose<br> Input, output daily you must choose.</p> The search for the “inputs” of secular artwork sometimes took a paranoid form—such as the belief in subliminal messages recorded in reverse, or in isolated frames from <i>Lion King</i> where smoke allegedly forms the word <i>sex</i> . Most often, however, the analysis was more direct. Portraying a behavior or describing a belief, unless accompanied immediately by a clear negative judgment, is an endorsement and a recommendation, and people who consume such messages will become more likely to behave and believe in that way.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/12/evangelical-christian/418236/">Read: Defining <em>evangelical</em></a><br><br> This theory underwrote the whole edifice of Christian contemporary music, which aimed to replace a particularly powerful avenue for negative messages. One of my running jokes for many years has been that all Top 40 music is effectively Christian contemporary music now; <i>American Idol</i> confirmed the hegemony of the “praise band” vocal style. More clear is the fact that all mainstream criticism—especially of film and television—is evangelical in form, if not in content. Every artwork is imagined to have a clear message; the portrayal of a given behavior or belief is an endorsement and a recommendation; consumption of artwork with a given message will directly result in the behaviors or beliefs portrayed. This is one of the few phenomena where the “both sides” cliché is true: Left-wing critics are just as likely to do this as their right-wing opponents. For every video of a right-wing provocateur like <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ynU-wVdesr0&amp;pp=ygUfYmVuIHNoYXBpcm8gYmFyYmllIG1vdmllIHJldmlldw%3D%3D">Ben Shapiro</a> decrying the woke excesses of <i>Barbie</i> , there is a review praising the Mattel product tie-in as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/jul/23/barbie-review-greta-gerwig-margot-robbie-ryan-riotous-candy-coloured-feminist-fable">a feminist fable</a> .<br><br> Here, however, I am more concerned with the critical practices of my comrades on the left. Among leftist publications, <i>Jacobin</i> stands out for its reductive and moralizing cultural coverage. Addressing the other major movie of this past weekend, for instance, the critic Eileen Jones worried <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jacobin.com/2023/07/christopher-nolan-oppenheimer-film-review">in a recent column</a> , “If you&#39;re already convinced of the dangers of nuclear war, superseded only by the ongoing end-times series of rolling climate catastrophes that now seem more likely to kill us all, this film is going to lack a certain urgency.” Sadly, instead of an educational presentation on nuclear war, film audiences will instead find a biopic that takes some liberties with its subject&#39;s life and character for the sake of creating a Hollywood blockbuster. Jones <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jacobin.com/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-mattel-consumerism-feminism">finds</a> more to like in <i>Barbie</i> , despite “the familiar, toothless, you-go-girl pseudo-feminist pieties that Mattel has been monetizing for decades, alongside the nostalgic how-can-our-consumer-products-be-bad affirmations of Barbie as some sort of magic, wholesomely progressive uniter of generations of mothers and daughters.”<br><br> This trend is not limited to one publication. It is pervasive in online culture, above all on social media. For instance, over coffee on the morning after the epic <i>Barbenheimer</i> Friday, I learned some disturbing facts about <i>Oppenheimer</i> on Twitter. At least one viewer was worried that the film about the man who created the nuclear bomb did not include <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/anthonyocampo/status/1682406287555055618">any Japanese characters</a> . Indeed, it did not even directly portray his invention&#39;s horrific consequences. Surely this aesthetic choice was meant to minimize his actions by rendering his victims invisible. (An article in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2023/07/who-are-the-japanese-in-christopher-nolans-oppenheimer.html"><i>New York</i> magazine</a> drew attention to the same absence.) I also <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/AlisaValdesRod1/status/1682167160364494849">learned</a> that the area surrounding <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tewawomenunited.org/2023/07/oppenheimer-and-the-other-side-of-the-story">Los Alamos was actually cleared of Indigenous and Hispanic residents</a> , another bit of history that is effectively erased by the film.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-nuclear-bomb-anxiety-nightmares/674795/">John Hendrickson: <em>Oppenheimer</em> nightmares? You&#39;re not alone.</a><br><br> Let&#39;s imagine, though, that those complaints had been anticipated and addressed. Let&#39;s imagine an entire subplot of a family going about their business in Hiroshima. We get to know and like them, to relate to them as our fellow human beings. Then, shockingly, they are incinerated by a nuclear blast. One can already hear the complaints. If the family were portrayed as too morally upstanding, it would be a dehumanizing portrayal that idealizes them as perfect victims. If they had moral flaws, the film would be subtly suggesting that they deserved their fate. And either way, the film would be attacked for offering up their suffering as a spectacle for our enjoyment. The same would go for the displaced population of Los Alamos—by portraying them as passive victims with no agency, critics would surely complain, the film would be reinscribing white authority.<br><br> Obviously leftists do not have to be as paranoid in their quest for messages supportive of the status quo as Christians playing their records backwards in the hopes of finding satanic content.  And of course we are a long way from having anything like the real-world thought police of Stalinism. During that dark era of Soviet history, writers and artists were expected to subscribe to the standards of socialist realism—which, instead of portraying the sordid and brutal reality of the present, anticipated the future reality of socialism by showing heroic workers building a utopian society. Those who fell short of those ideological expectations could expect a personal phone call from Comrade Stalin, if not worse. By contrast, it seems relatively harmless to hope that films and TV shows might reflect one&#39;s own politics and to lament when they fail to do so. Yet the very fact that the demand is so open-ended that it is impossible to imagine an artwork meeting its largely unstated and unarticulated standards shows that something has gone wrong here.<br><br> To be clear, I don&#39;t want to defend <i>Oppenheimer</i> in any way. I have not actually seen the film. Nothing anyone is saying is necessarily <i>wrong</i> ; it&#39;s just <i>not interesting</i> . Like most film and TV viewers, I read reviews because I want to decide whether or not to see a given movie or show, or else to think it through from a fresh perspective. For example, I note that <i>Oppenheimer</i> is very long—how is the pacing? Does it maintain a clear focus throughout, or does it indulge the common vice of biopics by trying to cram too much in? The type of critical literature that concerns me does not address such basic aesthetic questions, or does so only incidentally.<br><br> Even more insidiously, though, the logical goal of such very narrow standards could be to create artwork that is straightforward political propaganda. We&#39;ve seen how badly that turned out for the evangelicals (and, indeed, for the Stalinists). Even if we are unlikely to face the scourge of a Leninist equivalent to <i>VeggieTales</i> , however, this style of criticism infantilizes its audience members by assuming they are essentially ideology-processing machines—unlike the wise commentator who somehow manages to see through the deception.<br><br> Political problems cannot be solved on the aesthetic level. And it&#39;s much more likely that people are consuming politics as a kind of aesthetic performance or as a way of expressing aesthetic preferences than that they are somehow reading their politics off <i>Succession</i> , for example (“Welp, I guess rich people are good now. Better vote Republican!”). Just as the reduction of art to political propaganda leads to bad art, the aestheticization of politics leads to bad, irresponsible politics. That&#39;s because aesthetics and politics are not the same thing. They are not totally unrelated, obviously, but they are also and even primarily <i>different</i> . A political message <i>can</i> be part of an aesthetic effect, just as a political movement can benefit from an aesthetic appeal. But we get nowhere if we confuse or collapse these categories.<br><br> <small><i>This story was adapted from a post on Adam Kotsko&#39;s blog,</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://itself.blog/2023/07/22/we-are-all-evangelicals-now-a-nuclear-take/"><i>An Und Für Sich</i></a> <i>.</i></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-moralizing-reviews-social-media/674823/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-moralizing-reviews-social-media/674823/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[America Already Has an AI Underclass]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Search engines, ChatGPT, and other AI tools wouldn&#39;t function without an army of contractors. Now those workers say they&#39;re underpaid and mistreated. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/W9dDOpfZoxUtGyb25U2I5MMXY_M=/0x0:2160x2700/648x810/media/img/2023/07/24/ai_rater_f_3/original.jpg" alt="一只机械手投射出人头形状的阴影。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Joanne Imperio / The Atlantic</figcaption></figure> O <span class="smallcaps">n weekdays, between homeschooling</span> her two children, Michelle Curtis logs on to her computer to squeeze in a few hours of work. Her screen flashes with Google Search results, the writings of a Google chatbot, and the outputs of other algorithms, and she has a few minutes to respond to each—judging the usefulness of the blue links she&#39;s been provided, checking the accuracy of an AI&#39;s description of a praying mantis, or deciding which of two chatbot-written birthday poems is better. She never knows what she will have to assess in advance, and for the AI-related tasks, which have formed the bulk of her work since February, she says she has little guidance and not enough time to do a thorough job.<br><br> Curtis is an AI rater. She works for the data company Appen, which is subcontracted by Google to evaluate the outputs of the tech giant&#39;s AI products and search algorithm. Countless people do similar work around the world for Google; the ChatGPT-maker, OpenAI; and other tech <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/features/23764584/ai-artificial-intelligence-data-notation-labor-scale-surge-remotasks-openai-chatbots">firms</a> . Their human feedback plays a crucial role in developing chatbots, search engines, social-media feeds, and targeted-advertising systems—the most important parts of the digital economy.<br><br> Curtis told me that the job is grueling, underpaid, and poorly defined. Whereas Google has a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://static.googleusercontent.com/media/guidelines.raterhub.com/en/searchqualityevaluatorguidelines.pdf">176-page guide</a> for search evaluations, the instructions for AI tasks are relatively sparse, she said. For every task she performs that involves rating AI outputs, she is given a few sentences or paragraphs of vague, even convoluted instructions and as little as just a few minutes to fully absorb them before the time allotted to complete the task is up. Unlike a page of Google results, chatbots promise authoritative answers—offering the final, rather than first, step of inquiry, which Curtis said makes her feel a heightened moral responsibility to assess AI responses as accurately as possible. She dreads these timed tasks for the very same reason: “It&#39;s just not humanly possible to do in the amount of time that we&#39;re given.” On Sundays, she works a full eight hours. “Those long days can really wear on you,” she said.<br><br> Armughan Ahmad, Appen&#39;s CEO, told me through a spokesperson that the company “complies with minimum wages” and is investing in improved training and benefits for its workers; a Google spokesperson said Appen is solely responsible for raters&#39; working conditions and job training. For Google to mention these people at all is notable. Despite their importance to the generative-AI boom and tech economy more generally, these workers are almost never referenced in tech companies&#39; prophecies about the ascendance of intelligent machines. AI moguls describe their products as forces akin to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/03/ai-gpt4-technology-analogy/673509/">electricity</a> or <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/03/31/technology/sam-altman-open-ai-chatgpt.html">nuclear fission</a> , like facts of nature waiting to be discovered, and speak of “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/technology/elon-musks-ai-firm-xai-launches-website-2023-07-12/">maximally curious</a> ” machines that learn and grow on their own, like children. The human side of sculpting algorithms tends to be relegated to opaque descriptions of “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ai.meta.com/resources/models-and-libraries/llama/">human annotations</a> ” and “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.google.com/search/howsearchworks/how-search-works/rigorous-testing/#qualityTests">quality tests</a> ,” evacuated of the time and energy powering those annotations.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/google-search-generative-experience-content-creation/674674/">Read: Google&#39;s new search tool could eat the internet alive</a><br><br> The tech industry has a history of veiling the difficult, exploitative, and sometimes dangerous work needed to clean up its platforms and programs. But as AI rapidly infiltrates our daily lives, tensions between tech companies framing their software as self-propelling and the AI raters and other people actually pushing those products along have started to surface. In 2021, Appen raters began organizing with the Alphabet Workers Union-Communications Workers of America to push for greater recognition and compensation; Curtis joined its ranks last year. At the center of the fight is a big question: In the coming era of AI, can the people doing the tech industry&#39;s grunt work ever be seen and treated not as tireless machines but simply as what they are—human?<br><br> T <span class="smallcaps">he technical name</span> for the use of such ratings to improve AI models is <em>reinforcement learning with human feedback</em> , or RLHF. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://openai.com/research/instruction-following">OpenAI</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.deepmind.com/blog/building-safer-dialogue-agents">Google</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www-files.anthropic.com/production/images/Model-Card-Claude-2.pdf">Anthropic</a> , and other companies all use the technique. After a chatbot has processed massive amounts of text, human feedback helps fine-tune it. ChatGPT is impressive because using it feels like chatting with a human, but that pastiche does not naturally arise through ingesting data from <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/01/artificial-intelligence-ai-chatgpt-dall-e-2-learning/672754/">something like the entire internet</a> , an amalgam of recipes and patents and blogs and novels. Although AI programs are set up to be effective at pattern detection, they “don&#39;t have any sense of contextual understanding, no ability to parse whether AI-generated text looks more or less like what a human would have written,” Sarah Myers West, the managing director of the AI Now Institute, an independent research organization, told me. Only an actual person can make that call.<br><br> The program might write multiple recipes for chocolate cake, which a rater ranks and edits. Those evaluations and examples will inform the chatbot&#39;s statistical model of language and next-word predictions, which should make the program better at writing recipes in the style of a human, for chocolate cake and beyond. A person might check a chatbot&#39;s response for factual accuracy, rate how well it fits the prompt, or flag toxic outputs; subject experts can be particularly helpful, and they tend to be paid more.<br><br> Using human evaluations to improve algorithmic products is a fairly old practice at this point: Google and Facebook have been using them for almost a decade, if not more, to develop <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://support.google.com/websearch/answer/9281931">search engines</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.facebook.com/business/help/204798856225114?id=649869995454285">targeted ads</a> , and other products, Sasha Luccioni, an AI researcher at the machine-learning company Hugging Face, told me. The extent to which human ratings have shaped today&#39;s algorithms depends on who you ask, however. Major tech companies that design and profit from search engines, chatbots, and other algorithmic products tend to characterize the raters&#39; work as only one among many important aspects of building cutting-edge AI products. Courtenay Mencini, a Google spokesperson, told me that “ratings do not directly impact or solely train our algorithms. Rather, they&#39;re one data point … taken in aggregate with extensive internal development and testing.” OpenAI has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://openai.com/research/gpt-4">emphasized</a> that training on huge amounts of text, rather than RLHF, accounts for most of GPT-4&#39;s capabilities.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/sam-altman-openai-chatgpt-gpt-4/674764/">From the September 2023 issue: Does Sam Altman know what he&#39;s creating?</a><br><br> AI experts I spoke with outside these companies took a different stance. Targeted human feedback has been “the single most impactful change that made [current] AI models as good as they are,” allowing the leap from GPT-2&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/7/20953040/openai-text-generation-ai-gpt-2-full-model-release-1-5b-parameters">half-baked</a> emails to GPT-4&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/03/open-ai-gpt4-chatbot-technology-power/673421/">convincing essays</a> , Luccioni said. She and others argue that tech companies intentionally downplay the importance of human feedback. Such obfuscation “sockets away some of the most unseemly elements of these technologies,” such as hateful content and misinformation that humans have to identify, Myers West told me—not to mention the conditions the people work under. Even setting aside those elements, describing the extent of human intervention would risk dispelling the magical and marketable illusion of intelligent machines—a “ <em>Wizard of Oz</em> effect,” Luccioni said.<br><br> Despite tech companies&#39; stated positions, digging into their own press statements and research papers about AI reveals that they frequently do acknowledge the value of this human labor, if in broad terms. A Google blog post promoting a new chatbot last year, for instance, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.deepmind.com/blog/building-safer-dialogue-agents">said</a> that “to create safer dialogue agents, we need to be able to learn from human feedback.” Google has similarly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://blog.google/products/search/raters-experiments-improve-google-search/">described</a> human evaluations as necessary to its search engine. The company touts RLHF as “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/ai-machine-learning/google-cloud-launches-new-ai-models-opens-generative-ai-studio">particularly useful</a> ” for applying its AI services to industries such as health care and finance. Two lead researchers at OpenAI similarly described human evaluations as vital to training ChatGPT in an <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.technologyreview.com/2023/03/03/1069311/inside-story-oral-history-how-chatgpt-built-openai/">interview</a> with <em>MIT Technology Review</em> . The company stated elsewhere that GPT-4 exhibited “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2303.08774.pdf">large improvements</a> ” in accuracy after RLHF training and that human feedback was crucial to fine-tuning it. Meta&#39;s most recent language model, released this week, relies on “over 1 million new human annotations,” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ai.meta.com/resources/models-and-libraries/llama/">according to the company</a> .<br><br> To some extent, the significance of humans&#39; AI ratings is evident in the money pouring into them. One company that hires people to do RLHF and data annotation was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnbc.com/2023/05/09/sclae-ai-disruptor-50.html">valued</a> at more than $7 billion in 2021, and its CEO recently <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/alexandr_wang/status/1620934510820093952?lang=en">predicted</a> that AI companies will soon spend billions of dollars on RLHF, similar to their investment in computing power. The global market for labeling data used to train these models (such as tagging an image of a cat with the label “cat”), another part of the “ghost work” powering AI, could <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.technologyreview.com/2022/04/20/1050392/ai-industry-appen-scale-data-labels/">reach</a> nearly $14 billion by 2030, according to an estimate from April 2022, months before the ChatGPT gold rush began.<br><br> A <span class="smallcaps">ll of that money</span> , however, rarely seems to be reaching the actual people doing the ghostly labor. The contours of the work are starting to materialize, and the few public investigations into it are alarming: Workers in Africa are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/6275995/chatgpt-facebook-african-workers-union/">paid as little as $1.50 an hour</a> to check outputs for disturbing content that has reportedly left some of them with PTSD. Some contractors <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/features/23764584/ai-artificial-intelligence-data-notation-labor-scale-surge-remotasks-openai-chatbots">in the US</a> can earn only a couple of dollars above the minimum wage for repetitive, exhausting, and rudderless work. The pattern is similar to that of social-media content moderators, who can be paid a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/25/18229714/cognizant-facebook-content-moderator-interviews-trauma-working-conditions-arizona">tenth as much as software engineers</a> to scan traumatic content for hours every day. “The poor working conditions directly impact data quality,” Krystal Kauffman, a fellow at the Distributed AI Research Institute and an organizer of raters and data labelers on Amazon Mechanical Turk, a crowdsourcing platform, told me.<br><br> Stress, low pay, minimal instructions, inconsistent tasks, and tight deadlines—the sheer volume of data needed to train AI models almost necessitates a rush job—are a recipe for human error, according to Appen raters affiliated with the Alphabet Workers Union-Communications Workers of America and multiple independent experts. Documents <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-07-12/google-s-ai-chatbot-is-trained-by-humans-who-say-they-re-overworked-underpaid-and-frustrated">obtained</a> by <em>Bloomberg</em> , for instance, show that AI raters at Google have as little as three minutes to complete some tasks, and that they evaluate high-stakes responses, such as how to safely dose medication. Even OpenAI has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2303.08774.pdf">written</a> , in the technical report accompanying GPT-4, that “undesired behaviors [in AI systems] can arise when instructions to labelers were underspecified” during RLHF.<br><br> Tech companies have at times responded to these issues by stating that ratings are not the only way they check accuracy, that humans doing those ratings are paid <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/features/23764584/ai-artificial-intelligence-data-notation-labor-scale-surge-remotasks-openai-chatbots">adequately</a> based on their location and afforded proper training, and that viewing traumatic materials is not a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/25/18229714/cognizant-facebook-content-moderator-interviews-trauma-working-conditions-arizona">typical</a> experience. Mencini, the Google spokesperson, told me that Google&#39;s wages and benefits standards for contractors do not apply to raters, because they “work part-time from home, can be assigned to multiple companies&#39; accounts at a time, and do not have access to Google&#39;s systems or campuses.” In response to allegations of raters seeing offensive materials, she said that workers “select to opt into reviewing sensitive content, and can opt out freely at any time.” The companies also tend to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2023/06/14/google-ai-bard-raters-chatbot-accuracy/">shift blame</a> to their <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/6147458/facebook-africa-content-moderation-employee-treatment/">vendors</a> —Mencini, for instance, told me that “Google is simply not the employer of any Appen workers.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/07/generative-ai-human-culture-philosophy/674165/">Read: The coming humanist renaissance</a><br><br> Appen&#39;s raters told me that their working conditions do not align with various tech companies&#39; assurances—and that they hold Appen and Google responsible, because both profit from their work. Over the past year, Michelle Curtis and other raters have demanded more time to complete AI evaluations, benefits, better compensation, and the right to organize. The job&#39;s flexibility does have advantages, they told me. Curtis has been able to navigate her children&#39;s medical issues; another Appen rater I spoke with, Ed Stackhouse, said the adjustable hours afford him time to deal with a heart condition. But flexibility does not justify low pay and a lack of benefits, Shannon Wait, an organizer with the AWU-CWA, told me; there&#39;s nothing flexible about precarity.<br><br> The group made headway at the start of the year, when Curtis and her fellow raters received their first-ever raise. She now makes $14.50 an hour, up from $12.75—still below the minimum of $15 an hour that Google has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://about.google/extended-workforce/">promised</a> to its vendors, temporary staff, and contractors. The union continued raising concerns about working conditions; Stackhouse wrote a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/AlphabetWorkers/status/1658489222695915522">letter</a> to Congress about these issues in May. Then, just over two weeks later, Curtis, Stackhouse, and several other raters received an email from Appen stating, “Your employment is being terminated due to business conditions.”<br><br> The AWU-CWA suspected that Appen and Google were punishing the raters for speaking out. “The raters that were let go all had one thing in common, which was that they were vocal about working conditions or involved in organizing,” Stackhouse told me. Although Appen did suffer a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://s41256.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Appen_AR22_Interactive_v-final.pdf">drop</a> in revenue during the broader tech downturn last year, the company also had, and has, open job postings. Four weeks before the termination, Appen had sent an email offering cash incentives to work more hours and meet “a significant spike in jobs available since the beginning of year,” when the generative-AI boom was in full swing; just six days before the layoffs, Appen sent another email lauding “record-high production levels” and re-upping the bonus-pay offer. On June 14, the union filed a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nlrb.gov/case/32-CA-320053">complaint</a> with the National Labor Relations Board alleging that Appen and Google had <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2023/06/14/google-ai-bard-raters-chatbot-accuracy/">retaliated</a> against raters “by terminating six employees who were engaged in protected [labor] activity.”<br><br> Less than two weeks after the complaint was filed, Appen reversed its decision to fire Curtis, Stackhouse, and the others; their positions were reinstated with back pay. Ahmad, Appen&#39;s CEO, told me in an email that his company bases “employment decisions on business requirements” and is “happy that our business needs changed and we were able to hire back the laid off contributors.” He added, “Our policy is not to discriminate against employees due to any protected labor activities,” and that “we&#39;ve been actively investing in workplace enhancements like smarter training, and improved benefits.”<br><br> Mencini, the Google spokesperson, told me that “only Appen, as the employer, determines their employees&#39; working conditions,” and that “Appen provides job training for their employees.” As with compensation and training, Mencini deflected responsibility for the treatment of organizing workers as well: “We, of course, respect the labor rights of Appen employees to join a union, but it&#39;s a matter between them and their employer, Appen.”<br><br> T <span class="smallcaps">hat AI purveyors would obscure</span> the human labor undergirding their products is predictable. Much of the data that train AI models is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.noemamag.com/the-exploited-labor-behind-artificial-intelligence/">labeled by people</a> making poverty wages, many of them located in the global South. Amazon deliveries are cheap in part because <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/06/15/us/amazon-workers.html">working conditions</a> in the company&#39;s warehouses subsidize them. Social media is usable and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2022/10/28/23428132/elon-musk-twitter-acquisition-problems-speech-moderation">desirable</a> because of armies of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/25/social-media-companies-are-outsourcing-their-dirty-work-philippines-generation-workers-is-paying-price/">content moderators</a> also largely in the global South. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/resources/cloud-computing-dictionary/what-is-cloud-computing">“Cloud” computing</a> , a cornerstone of Amazon&#39;s and Microsoft&#39;s businesses, takes place in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.blackstone.com/insights/article/greg-blank-mike-forman-on-demand-for-data-centers/">giant data centers</a> .<br><br> AI raters might be understood as an extension of that cloud, treated not as laborers with human needs so much as productive units, carbon transistors on a series of fleshly microchips—objects, not people. Yet even microchips take up space; they require not just electricity but also ventilation to keep from overheating. The Appen raters&#39; termination and reinstatement is part of “a more generalized pattern within the tech industry of engaging in very swift retaliation against workers” when they organize for better pay or against ethical concerns about the products they work on, Myers West, of the AI Now Institute, told me.<br><br> Ironically, one crucial bit of human labor that AI programs have proved unable to automate is their own training. Human subjectivity and prejudice have long migrated their way into algorithms, and those flaws mean machines may not be able to perfect themselves. Various attempts to train AI models with other AI models have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/generative-ai-future-training-models/674478/">bred further bias</a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.03277">worsened</a> performance, though a few have shown <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2305.03047.pdf">limited</a> success. “I can&#39;t imagine that we will be able to replicate [human intervention] with current AI approaches,” Hugging Face&#39;s Luccioni told me in an email; Ahmad said that “using AI to train AI can have dire consequences as it pertains to the viability and credibility of this technology.” The tech industry has so far failed to purge the ghosts haunting its many other machines and services—the people organizing on warehouse floors, walking out of corporate headquarters, unionizing overseas, and leaking classified documents. Appen&#39;s raters are proving that, even amid the generative-AI boom, humanity may not be so easily exorcized.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-chatbot-human-evaluator-feedback/674805/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-chatbot-human-evaluator-feedback/674805/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[American Girlhood Culture Is Really Strange]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> <em>Barbie</em> purports to be critical of Mattel while being enthusiastically sponsored by Mattel. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/x-xsz1KnKkOjhSGRth3GJNsRuTg=/235x0:2763x1422/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/MCDBARB_WB037/original.jpg" alt="玛格特·罗比饰演芭比娃娃的形象" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>华纳兄弟。</figcaption></figure> In the 2000s, male artists routinely excavated the popular culture of their boyhood for imaginative repurposing in their art. Michael Chabon&#39;s novel <i>The Amazing Adventures of Kavalier &amp; Clay</i> traces the lives of two men who become comic-book creators. In Jonathan Lethem&#39;s <i>The</i> <i>Fortress of Solitude</i> , two boys find a magic ring they use to take on superpowers; the title itself evokes the fictional fortress of Superman. Back then, I remember feeling that the equivalent was not possible for women artists, that the popular culture of American girlhood (horses, dolls, gymnastics) was still considered silly, juvenile—impossible to recuperate as adult art worth taking seriously.<br><br> Greta Gerwig seems at last a counterexample. Her entire career as a filmmaker has, in a sense, been a campaign to make art of girlhood materials. Her 2019 film, <i>Little Women</i> , remakes the 19th-century girlhood classic, rendering it freshly urgent for a 21st-century audience. (“I&#39;ve been angry every day of my life,” Marmee, the saintly mother of the novel, says in Gerwig&#39;s version.) Her directorial debut, <i>Lady Bird</i> (2017), captures the angst of a 17-year-old girl&#39;s coming-of-age in all its granular reality.<br><br> And now here is the <i>Barbie</i> juggernaut. <i>Barbie</i> dominated the box office on its opening weekend, grossing a stunning $155 million: a post-pandemic high, and the biggest opening for any feature film directed by a woman. Grown-up art about girlhood really can be an economic and cultural powerhouse. In the past week, women I barely know and women I have known for years have texted me their excitement about the film—and then shared their response, which has been in many cases the same: They <i>loved</i> watching the film, and yet more than one felt oddly disappointed by it.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/">Read: Greta Gerwig&#39;s lessons from Barbie land</a><br><br> Perhaps this is because, as the critic Dana Stevens <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/culture/2023/07/barbie-movie-2023-margot-robbie-ryan-gosling-review.html">noted in <i>Slate</i></a> , <i>Barbie</i> “never completely resolves the paradox at its heart”: The movie purports to be critical of Mattel while being enthusiastically sponsored by Mattel. The constraint is so obvious that Gerwig tries to turn it into a joke. The plot hinges on the conceit that all the Barbies mistakenly believe that their existence has turned the “real” world into a feminist paradise. Gerwig knows that no one wants to watch a hectoring film about how the doll is bad for girls&#39; self-image. So she subversively jokes about the insidious side of corporate culture while visually celebrating the Barbieness of Barbie. In this way, <i>Barbie</i> really is, if not a wholly successful film, certainly a powerful monument to the strangeness of American girl culture, which remains impoverished in its vision of what young girls are and want.<br><br> At once a commercial for a toy and a delicious romp through the pleasures of childhood play, <i>Barbie</i> sits uneasily at the intersection of reality, fantasy, and critique. It is joyous, winking, frothily cinematic. There are lavish costumes, deftly choreographed dance numbers, and aesthetically sophisticated visual puns. Barbie, played by Margot Robbie, is wryly known as “Stereotypical Barbie”; blond and perfect, she showers and drinks without ever getting wet, walks on her toes, floats down from her bedroom to the street as if held by an invisible girl&#39;s hand. The script is peppered with genuinely incisive and funny skewers of gender stereotypes. A key moment in the plot involves the Barbies allowing the Kens to “sing at them” while playing guitars; the preposition is pure genius.<br><br> Like many women before it, <i>Barbie</i> tries to be many things to many people. One trailer&#39;s tag line was “If you love Barbie, this movie is for you. If you hate Barbie, this movie is for you.” The line gets at the challenge here, adjacent to the one Stevens identified: How do you make a film for an audience that remains fiercely divided about the material you&#39;re writing about?<br><br> This conflict, one might say, is precisely what forces Stereotypical Barbie out of her dreamy pink home on a quest to understand a series of strange phenomena: cellulite, cold showers, melancholy. We meet Barbie in Barbie Land, where women rule, literally. There is a Barbie president; there are nine Supreme Court Barbies. Kens are reduced to supporting roles. They wait for Barbies to kiss them, notice them, long for them. But when Barbie begins having relentless thoughts of death, she and one of the Kens, played to deliciously banal perfection by Ryan Gosling, enter “reality.” It isn&#39;t the paradise she expected; men ogle her and a girl calls her a “fascist.” As reality&#39;s reality dawns on Barbie, she articulates a set of feelings at once amusingly framed and horrifying to witness: “I feel … ill at ease,” she says. “I&#39;m getting undertones of violence.” (Cue women squirming in the audience.) Meanwhile, Ken is radicalized by his experience: He likes the attention he gets. He sees a new world, one where men are not second-class citizens, and returns to Barbie Land to brainwash the Barbies into serving the Kens. The former Supreme Court justices are now cheerleaders.<br><br> Rather than get angry at what has happened to Barbie Land, Barbie is crushed. She stops wearing makeup and lies on the floor in despair, waiting for another Barbie to take the lead in fixing her society. And so the second half of the film tells the somewhat incoherent story of her evolution from thinking she is not “good enough” to becoming a woman bent on self-determination. In reality, she befriends a real woman named Gloria (America Ferrara), who delivers an impassioned motivational speech about how hard it is to be a woman in a world that demands contradictory things: to care tirelessly for your children but not talk about them too much; to act when action seems fruitless.<br><br> The challenge that Barbie, as a cultural object, presents Gerwig is how to mine the performative pleasures of clothes and dance numbers alongside the travesties of modern American culture while framing the story as if the two are wholly disconnected. She&#39;s trying to show what it might really be like to go from a dream land to contemporary America, where <i>Roe v. Wade</i> has been overturned, parents don&#39;t automatically get parental leave after the birth of a child, and most CEOs of corporations (including Mattel) are still men.<br><br> <i>Barbie</i> is at once radical and conventional. It is radical in its light indictment of the patriarchy: One of the very best lines of cultural criticism I&#39;ve heard in ages comes when Ken says, “To be honest, when I found out the patriarchy wasn&#39;t about horses I lost interest.” (The movie might be best read as a brilliant portrait of aggrieved far-right masculinity.) It is somewhat more conventional in its vision of a dream girlhood and its idea of what Barbie <i>is</i> . And perhaps here is where Mattel&#39;s influence is strongest. Despite the presence of Doctor Barbies and Supreme Court Barbies, Gerwig&#39;s Barbies still largely conform to rigid beauty norms; a night of fun is a dance number in glittery and sexy clothes; and no conflict ever occurs, because the days are coated in a vapid gloss of fashion and pink plastic that corporate America has always been selling girls. This is the vision that led my second-wave-feminist mother to ban Barbie from our house. When my aunt gave me two for my fifth birthday, they mysteriously disappeared a few days later.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">Read: The surprising key to understanding the Barbie film</a><br><br> To some degree, this vapidity is Gerwig&#39;s point: Barbie must leave Barbie Land, as all girls must, to confront a messier and more complex reality. And yet <i>Barbie</i> skirts the deep cognitive dissonance the doll inspires in many girls. Thanks to my mother&#39;s ban, I played with Barbie only at friends&#39; houses. I recall finding the doll boring, because she was relentlessly tethered to <i>our</i> world and to the culture&#39;s expectations for adult me, ones that didn&#39;t yet interest me (boys, houses, Malibu). Instead of playing Barbie, my friends and I disfigured her so she looked like the film&#39;s Weird Barbie (Kate MacKinnon), a doll with a 1980s punk haircut who&#39;s out of step with all the others. Like the montage in the film showing what a girl did to Weird Barbie, we chopped off the doll&#39;s hair down to chunky sprouts, turned her head backward, covered her face in green marker. In the film&#39;s lingo, Weird Barbie is weird because girls have “played too hard” with her, a telling evasion. Weird Barbie is not weird because someone played too hard with her. Weird Barbie is weird, as Gerwig surely knows, because some girl used her to express all her frustration at the confection of materialism and reductive beauty norms. Weird Barbie wants to raze Barbie Land, not just help Stereotypical Barbie see reality for what it is.<br><br> <i>Barbie</i> is a fascinating moment in the ascendance of girl culture, a brilliantly twisty dive into the core of the contradictory scripts shaping what it is like to grow up as a girl in America. One of those scripts teaches that girlhood isn&#39;t a space of imaginative autonomy but a kind of prep school for a conventional consumer adulthood that will be shaped by hair appointments, shopping, and a job. Despite the constraints she faces, Gerwig tries to invoke a more capacious script for girlhood at the film&#39;s end, in a beautiful montage of girls playing around the world, in muted visuals that starkly contrast with the Technicolor Barbie world. If the film emerges aesthetically scathed, that doesn&#39;t mean it is a failure. I left delighted by how much Gerwig had achieved through humor, and by the conviction that <i>Barbie</i> can only help make room for more films by women about women. The film&#39;s tag line is right. One can hate Barbie and still be glad this movie was made, because here it is at last: a movie full of jokes for us, the women and girls in the room. In that sense, nothing about <i>Barbie</i> is silly or juvenile.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-girlhood-greta-gerwig/674821/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-girlhood-greta-gerwig/674821/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Greta Gerwig’s Lessons From Barbie Land]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> “你对你感兴趣的东西感兴趣，而我对女人感兴趣。” <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/HQCGi0UhG3lSR1FkaVTU_9EwfVQ=/0x0:2160x2700/648x810/media/img/2023/07/25/greta_gerwig_1/original.jpg" alt="格蕾塔·葛韦格的黑白肖像，双手捧着脸" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乔迪·罗加克 / Trunk Archive</figcaption></figure><strong><em>本文包含电影</em></strong><strong>《芭比娃娃》的剧透<em>。</em></strong><br><br>当我问起有关肯的问题时，我与格蕾塔·葛韦格的电话就挂断了。当<em>《芭比娃娃》</em>的编剧兼导演回来时，她不知道发生了什么。我建议，<em>仅仅</em>提及肯——瑞恩·高斯林扮演的那个憔悴且被忽视的娃娃——当然会导致某种失败。葛韦格同意了。 “世界就像，<em>我不在乎</em>，”她开玩笑说。<br><br>但全世界都非常关心他所出演的电影。自周五上映以来， <em>《芭比娃娃》的</em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2023/07/24/1189760422/barbie-oppenheimer-box-office-ticket-sales">表现超出了预期</a>，成为第一部首周末票房超过 1 亿美元的工作室喜剧，并创下北美首映票房最高纪录。一位女导演。观众——其中许多人从头到脚都穿着粉红色——挤满了剧院，据报道甚至导致剧院到周六晚上就<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/23/movies/barbie-oppenheimer-box-office-numbers.html">没有优惠了</a>。<br><br> <em>《芭比娃娃</em>》的大规模首映使这部电影成为葛韦格作为导演迄今为止最成功的票房作品。然而，这部电影完全符合葛韦格的全部作品：就像 2017 年的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/11/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-review/544721/"><em>《伯德小姐</em></a>》和 2019 年的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/12/greta-gerwigs-little-women-finally-gives-amy-her-due/603886/"><em>《小妇人》</em></a>一样，它深入思考了如何表达女性气质。葛韦格与搭档诺亚·鲍姆巴赫 (Noah Baumbach) 共同创作的<em>《芭比娃娃》的分量</em>可能出乎意料地沉重。在闪闪发光的服装和盛大派对的背后是一个可爱的人文主义故事，它研究产品如何影响和反映我们是谁。<br><br>也许这听起来很崇高，但考虑一下芭比（玛格特·罗比饰）和肯在现实世界中的冒险，这在电影中不仅仅是鱼出水狂欢的机会。两人肩负着在一个对待男性和女性不同的社会中生存的艰巨任务：芭比作为一个代表理想女性的玩具，与她有缺陷的目的作斗争；肯（Ken）是专为芭比娃娃的手臂糖果而创造的，他通过观察人类第一次尝到了力量的滋味，并误解了他所看到的。<em>芭比娃娃</em>既顽皮又深思熟虑，充满笑话，常常超现实的奇观包裹着真诚、女权主义和彻底的葛韦格风格的核心。<br><br>然而，当我们周五早上交谈时，葛韦格并不知道<em>芭比娃娃</em>会如何着陆。正如她所说，她预计自己会“整天焦虑不安”，并且渴望聊天，而不是担心电影的反响。我们讨论了她电影中的主题，以及她在芭比乐园的经历教会了她什么。 （别担心，Ken 的粉丝们。我们最终会找到他的。）<br><br><em>为了篇幅和清晰度，本次对话已被编辑。</em><br><br><strong>雪莉·李：</strong>这部<em>芭比娃娃</em>电影中有很多关于自我价值的重要想法，以及我们消费的东西（或者玩玩偶的东西）如何影响我们成为什么样的人。我注意到一个小女孩在放映时问了很多问题；她似乎对那些令人兴奋的主题感到有点困惑，但玩得很开心，尤其是当娃娃们唱歌跳舞时。所以我很好奇：当你和诺亚写这部电影时，你把谁想象成你的观众？<br><br><strong>格蕾塔·葛韦格：</strong>我并没有强烈的感觉，<em>这是给孩子们的东西；这是给孩子们看的。这是成人的东西</em>。我知道有些东西更令人兴奋，但当我回顾小时候的观看经历时，往往那些超出我范围的东西是最引人注目的，因为它们感觉就像一扇小窗户，让我进入了我所看到的世界。正在兴起。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>比如什么？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>这是一个非常奇怪、非常具体的记忆，但当我五岁的时候，我爸爸在纽约工作，我和妈妈得到了去<em>吉普赛</em>的加急票。我大部分都听不懂，但是当吉普赛<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_wErVF7QwIY&amp;ab_channel=ProjectUnleash">在滑稽俱乐部表演</a>时，这些脱衣舞娘穿着闪闪发光的老式脱衣舞服装，我很喜欢。我不明白发生了什么，但我们得到了一本很大的纪念书，我记得只是研究了所有脱衣舞娘所在的页面，因为我认为它们是<em>如此</em>美丽。我没有任何感觉他们被客观化了。我只是喜欢他们穿着这些漂亮、闪闪发光的衣服和大头饰。我可能有很多这样的回忆。<br><br><strong>李：</strong> <em>《伯德小姐》</em>是根据你自己的经历写的， <em>《小妇人</em>》是你从小就喜欢看的书，小时候也玩过芭比娃娃。用你的电影来重温童年的试金石对你来说是一个有意的选择吗？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>老实说，在制作它们的过程中，我一直隐藏着一些东西，因为从表面上看，它们看起来很不同。但现在我看完了这个，我发现他们都在围绕着这个想法。 [<em>笑。</em> 】 你对你感兴趣的东西感兴趣，我对女人感兴趣。但我也认为——这听起来有点愚蠢——我的一个痴迷，可以说是，我真的有点不敢相信我们生活在线性时间里。 [<em>笑。</em> ] 这真是令人震惊。显然，当你有一个孩子时，你会与这个孩子紧密相连，但你在生活中也可以与它相连。<br><br>我认为，在试图将它们整合在一起并了解你现在在哪里以及你曾经去过哪里的过程中，总是会感到<em>痛苦</em>。显然，这就是我改编<em>《小妇人》</em>的方式，因为我突然<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/12/greta-gerwigs-little-women-finally-gives-amy-her-due/603886/">以一种我年轻时从未见过的方式将这些角色视为</a>成年人。 <em>《伯德小姐》</em>是一个关于一名高中生的故事，有些事情你觉得很重要，比如舞会，但实际上这是关于你的母亲和你的<em>离开</em>。这是我回归的话题，因为无论如何，电影本质上就是一个时间胶囊，所以它已经及时处理了。这就是我在智力和艺术上感兴趣的东西，而媒介本身似乎已经嵌入了这一点。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/12/greta-gerwigs-little-women-finally-gives-amy-her-due/603886/">阅读：格蕾塔·葛韦格的<em>《小妇人》</em>终于给了艾米应得的</a><br><br><strong>李：</strong>也许更好的说法是：你的电影都是关于女孩如何学习成为女人的。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>哦，<em>是的</em>！<br><br><strong>李：</strong>我是不是把事情想得太简单了？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>不，我喜欢它！那好美丽。 [<em>笑。</em> ] 不过，也许这就是你永远要做的事情。我不知道那是你到达的地方。这当然与年龄无关，因为它永远在展开。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>那么，你对少女时代最关心的是什么，拍这些电影也许可以帮助你理解？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>嗯，把它拆开是很困难的，但对我来说，这很大程度上与代际对话有关。当我想到我的祖母、我的母亲、我的时候，女性的生活已经发生了如此巨大的变化，我不知道接下来会发生什么变化，但我们不断互相学习。再过一周我就满 40 岁了，我开始以一种美妙的方式感觉到，我属于年轻女性回望的那一代，这种感觉美妙又奇怪。我确实认为这是一种让我能够深入地参与对话的方式，让我感觉值得拥有，无论是女性气质、人格还是线性时间中的存在。 [<em>笑。</em> ] 线性时间是我真正的一个难题。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>你说过制作这部电影就像你制作的任何其他电影一样个人化。有没有一个场景让你觉得这部电影对你来说非常个人化？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>从<em>芭比娃娃</em>徽标的字体（我一直被泡泡字母版本所吸引，部分原因是我在玩具“反”斗城看到的那个字体）到凯特·麦金农（Kate McKinnon）的角色非常重要这一事实，一切都包罗万象。反映了我拥有的芭比娃娃，一个被人喜爱的娃娃，但在盒子里不再处于原始完美的状态。芭比在长凳上看到的那个女人是我的朋友，杰出的服装设计师安·罗斯。我一直在思考面孔，当你看着她的面孔时，我想你看到了一种感觉就像是一种生活，而那个年龄不仅在其持续时间上有价值。<br><br> [当芭比娃娃和她的创造者牵手时]，所有这些视频剪辑都是从所有参与这部电影的人那里拍摄的——女性、母亲、姐妹、女儿、朋友。我坚信，即使你不知道电影中的内容，我认为你也能感受到它们。我一直很喜欢在<em>《好家伙》</em>中，马丁·斯科塞斯的母亲扮演妈妈。你不知道那是他的妈妈，但你觉得她就是那个人，而且感觉很私人。在某种程度上，这与一个孩子看电影时无法理解每一个参考内容，但以某种方式<em>感受到</em>它并没有什么不同。其中嵌入的个人信息是人们无意识收集的一部分。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>说到那些视频片段，我们再谈谈结局。你能告诉我关于让芭比娃娃和肯夫妇达成的决定吗？这不是一个最终的解决方案，而是一种缓和的方式？伊萨·雷饰演的芭比总统不允许肯在最高法院任职。他们还在想办法。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>我们<em>都</em>还在想办法——这只是其中的一部分。但我唯一能给任何人的就是他们仍然处于混乱之中。也许这对肯斯来说会好一点。你不想告诉人们如何观看事物，但在电影的结尾，制作设计将肯的一些迷恋融入了芭比乐园。就像，完美​​并不像开始将所有东西混合在一起那样美丽。我记得当我们去拍摄结局时，当我们都走在片场时，我们就像，<em>这是有史以来最美丽的</em>。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>你能告诉我为什么肯最终拒绝父权制吗？有趣的是，他承认他不明白。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong> [<em>沉默</em>]<br><br><strong>李：</strong>哦，不。格蕾塔，我失去你了吗？你好？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>嗨，好吧，我不知道发生了什么事。它就这样消失了。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>没关系。我觉得很有趣的是，一个关于肯的问题导致你挂断了电话。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong> [<em>笑。</em> ] 世界就像是，“我不在乎。”<br><br><strong>李：</strong>是的，“我们继续吧。”所以我想问：肯实际上并不想接管芭比乐园的想法从何而来？这部电影小心翼翼地将他描绘成一个被误导的反派，而不是一个怀恨在心的对手。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>嗯，在某种程度上，你会无意识地做事情，然后再将它们拼凑起来，但有一个元素让你感觉最后，你想要从自己手中被拯救出来。我猜它的黑暗反乌托邦版本是<em>《蝇王》</em> ，就像《野孩子》一样。他们是洋娃娃，但在心理上他们也是孩子。<br><br>事实上，我想到了我的继子。当他年轻的时候，他只是不睡觉。有一次，我走进他的卧室，他站在床上，把他的毛绒玩具扔来扔去，他尖叫道：“我希望有人能让我停下来！”它是如此纯粹[<em>笑</em>]，就像，实际上，他是对的！他希望有人能让他停下来。当瑞恩·高斯林和我谈论他将如何演绎结局时，我谈到了很多关于我 4 岁儿子的事。如果他哭了，你说：“哈罗德，我们不得不离开公园，你感到不安吗？”他会说：“是啊啊，是啊啊。”就像，他承认[他的悲伤]，但即使只是这样做也<em>很难</em>，那种情感的品质。<br><br>显然，这些系统对男性来说也很糟糕。当<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">美国发表美丽的演讲</a>时，我只是在抽泣，然后我环顾四周，发现片场里每个人都在哭。男人们也在哭，因为他们有自己的演讲，他们觉得自己永远无法发表，你知道吗？他们有自己的双钢丝，这也很痛苦。其中一些结构就是，你知道，“有人让我停下来！”我想这就是肯背后的感觉。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">阅读：理解<em>芭比</em>电影的令人惊讶的关键</a><br><br><strong>李：</strong>这是一部如此庞大的电影，也是你职业生涯中压力很大的时刻。作为一个电影人，你现在掌握着很大的权力，我想问你打算用它做什么？<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong> [<em>笑。</em> ]<em>我想做什么？</em>成为一名电影制片人是一件了不起的事情，因为拍电影很困难，你永远无法真正登上山顶。因为无论你接下来要制作什么，你都还没有制作过——所以你会学到关于<em>这部</em>电影你不知道的东西，你知道吗？这很困难，但这也是吸引力的一部分。但是，如果你幸运的话，你只会每两年、三年、四年拍一部电影。所以，如果你开始计算人生，你就会意识到，<em>我要做什么，拍 15 部电影？</em>你知道，不是太多。但如果我幸运的话，我就能过上一种像我希望做的任何事情一样有意义的生活。我<em>确实</em>想在 60 多岁和 70 多岁时拍电影，如果上帝愿意，也许我会在 80 多岁时拍一些极其奇怪的电影。<br><br><strong>李：</strong>既然你已经完成了大预算工作室的主力，你认为你的故事讲述会如何发展？我想你并不总是在做生活中的数学。<br><br><strong>葛韦格：</strong>我希望能够制作各种规模的电影。我喜欢拥有制作微小东西的技能，也喜欢拥有用最大的画笔绘画的技能。它总是关于什么能给你最大的创造性自由，这可能意味着不同的事情。<br><br>我也感到非常幸运，能够成长为更大的人。我在 20 多岁的时候与人共同编剧、共同导演、演过很多戏，我就是利用这些来开始执导的。 <em>《小妇人》</em>是一个中间步骤，当我想到年轻的电影制作人时，取决于你想做什么，如果你有兴趣看看它如何扩展或收缩，那么这些中级电影的制作是令人难以置信的。我非常感激我能做到这一点，因为没有它我就不可能做到<em>这一点</em>。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 18:24:05 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-greta-gerwig-interview/674817/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Oppenheimer’s Cry of Despair in The Atlantic]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在美国与苏联军备竞赛开始之际，这位伟大的科学家所能做的就是祈求希望。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/AjNA1aT674UuHHRmJHHbtxriWlM=/0x0:3596x2023/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/opp_atlwriter/original.jpg" alt="J·罗伯特·奥本海默抽烟" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>环球图片/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>1949 年 2 月，曼哈顿计划洛斯阿拉莫斯实验室前主任 J. 罗伯特·奥本海默 (J. Robert Oppenheimer) 在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1949/02/the-open-mind/305431/">这本杂志</a>上写下了一场可怕的失败。自从曼哈顿计划在新墨西哥州引爆第一颗原子弹以来，已经过去了近四年。爆炸向周围的山脉发出了紫色的光芒，并从沙漠地面升起一道 40,000 英尺高的火柱、烟雾和碎片。但对奥本海默来说，余辉很快就暗淡了，取而代之的是存在主义的头号宿醉。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1949/02/the-open-mind/305431/">1949 年 2 月起：J. 罗伯特·奥本海默 (J. Robert Oppenheimer) 的《开放思想》</a><br><br>克里斯托弗·诺兰的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-review-christopher-nolan/674749/">新奥本海默传记片中</a>最令人心碎的部分发生在希里安·墨菲饰演的这位伟大科学家开始经历困扰他余生的幻灭感时。当他看着两枚炸弹从他的沙漠实验室开往日本的卡车上隆隆作响时，任何认为它们的可怕威力在他控制之下的幻想都被戳破了。三位一体测试三周后，广岛遭到轰炸。在影片中，生病的奥本海默将目光从受害者毁容的照片上移开。就像诺兰的镜头一样，让人不忍直视。<br><br>奥本海默后来说，通过原子弹，物理学家开始了解罪恶。从知识之树上摘下危险的果实后，他们把自己——以及全人类——托付给了一个堕落的世界，不断遭受自我灭绝的可能性的折磨。战争刚结束时，奥本海默安慰自己，或者也许是欺骗自己，他的发明的世界末日潜力可以而且将会得到遏制，部分通过他的努力。<br><br>奥本海默有理由相信他的影响力。公众接受了他的个人传奇：出于对拥有核武器的希特勒的恐惧，他冒险进入了看不见的原子领域，并带着巨大的力量回来了，能够阻止战争感冒，让儿子回到母亲身边。他身上堆满了荣誉。在诺兰的电影中，我们看到奥本海默被争取担任一个豪华角色：普林斯顿大学高级研究所所长，阿尔伯特·爱因斯坦的学术故乡。奥本海默还担任负责向美国原子能委员会提供建议的委员会主席。 During the latter half of the 1940s, his pronouncements on matters of science had a singular gravitas. “Certainly he knows as much about the potential of atomic energy as any living American,” reads an editor&#39;s note atop his essay for <em>The Atlantic</em> .<br><br> What did he do with this outsize voice? He opposed the development of a much more powerful, second-generation atomic weapon—the hydrogen bomb, which Edward Teller called the “super”—in part because he was concerned it would accelerate an arms race with the Soviet Union. He also lent his prestige and credibility to ongoing efforts to avoid that arms race altogether. He helped draft the proposals that evolved into the Baruch Plan, an arms-control regime that the United States put before the United Nations. Under the latter&#39;s direction, all countries would forfeit their atomic-weapons programs, and atomic energy would be a global collective good, administered by a centralized regulatory body at the UN, over which no country would enjoy a veto.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/07/us-nuclear-strategy-cold-war-russia/638441/">Read: We have no nuclear strategy</a><br><br> After the final failure of these proposals at the UN, in 1948, Oppenheimer turned, as one does, to <em>The Atlantic</em> . His essay is a fascinating historical artifact and act of public grief. Titled “The Open Mind,” it lays out Oppenheimer&#39;s account of the back-and-forth over arms-control proposals. Soviet leaders had voted against them, but their response had not been wholly negative. They agreed that all countries should dismantle their atomic-weapons programs and that atomic energy should fall under international oversight. But they objected, perhaps understandably, to America&#39;s insistence on keeping its weapons program running until the new system was functional. They wanted President Harry Truman to disarm first, a condition that he could not abide.<br><br> During the Manhattan Project, Oppenheimer&#39;s powers of foresight had failed him. However accurate his calculations concerning the innards of the atom, he&#39;d misjudged what would happen geopolitically after he and his colleagues wrenched it apart. Out of naivete, or the expedient blindness of ambition, or some combination of the two, he may have believed that he could stop its further use after the Nazis had been defeated, or that the terrifying spectacle of the bomb would eventually lead to a renunciation of ever larger weapons and wars.<br><br> In 1949, he understood that no such renunciation was in store. “We see no clear course before us that would persuade the governments of the world to join with us” in atomic disarmament, he wrote. This time, the implications were obvious, and they implicated America, which, as Oppenheimer laments, “responded by adopting some of the very measures that we had hoped might be universally renounced.” The mass manufacture of the atomic bomb was under way and American scientists had clear orders to put the new physics in service of even more destructive weapons.<br><br> Oppenheimer saw a cosmically bleak arms race taking shape, and this time his  foresight proved accurate. Within months, the Soviet Union successfully tested its first atomic bomb, and only three years later, in 1952, the United States detonated a hydrogen bomb roughly 500 times as powerful as the one that had largely destroyed Nagasaki. The Soviets followed suit a few years later, and by the time of Oppenheimer&#39;s death, in 1967, the two countries had nearly 40,000 nuclear weapons between them, many of them <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/06/ai-warfare-nuclear-weapons-strike/673780/">set on a hair trigger</a> .<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/06/ai-warfare-nuclear-weapons-strike/673780/">Read: Never give artificial intelligence the nuclear codes</a><br><br> Oppenheimer knew that he&#39;d helped to conjure this world into existence. He sought to prepare our readers for its horrors. In the main, his advice was to not lose hope, and to remember that our imagination of the future is limited. Oppenheimer was perhaps heartened by the quantum world, shot through as it is with uncertainty, that had captivated him in his youth. He seemed to draw strength from a belief that the macro world of human affairs is likewise contingent, such that nothing about our fate is ever settled.<br><br> Oppenheimer quotes from a speech that Abraham Lincoln gave in Baltimore three years into the Civil War. At the beginning of that conflict, few expected that “domestic slavery would be much affected,” Lincoln said, and yet it had been. Reality is unpredictable; it will surprise you. Lincoln reminded Oppenheimer that surprises swing both ways. A world that appears to be fallen can sometimes veer toward moral progress.<br><br> We have seen such swerves before, even in the nuclear realm. By the 1980s, enormous arsenals of nuclear weapons appeared to be a fact of life on planet Earth. In 1986, the Soviet Union&#39;s stockpile reached an all-time high of about 40,000 warheads, and the United States had more than 20,000. Very few people imagined that the end of the Cold War was imminent. Nor could many have guessed that in 1991, George HW Bush and Mikhail Gorbachev would sign the Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty, the first in an extraordinary sequence of agreements that shrank the two countries&#39; arsenals to less than a quarter of their previous size.<br><br> Bush and Gorbachev were wise to seize the day, because that era&#39;s peace—and its clean two-party strategic symmetry—proved ephemeral. The specter of nuclear annihilation has since returned with force to the global collective psyche. Vladimir Putin has invoked it in speeches about his <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://Read:%20What%20if%20Russia%20uses%20nuclear%20weapons%20in%20Ukraine?">invasion of Ukraine</a> . China has built up an arsenal that may be large enough to destroy every major American city.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/06/russia-ukraine-nuclear-weapon-us-response/661315/">Read: What if Russia uses nuclear weapons in Ukraine?</a><br><br> As Oppenheimer well understood, there is no <em>technological</em> reason that world-threatening stockpiles of nuclear weapons will not be with us for hundreds of thousands of years. To keep large numbers of them in place for that long, in a strategic setting where any small exchange could very easily become a large one, is to play a fool&#39;s game. No one should feel safe because seven decades have passed without another incident of nuclear warfare; that sample size is too small.<br><br> Beyond advising hope, Oppenheimer didn&#39;t offer much guidance as to how we might dismantle the sword of Damocles that he helped to string up above human civilization. A notorious dandy and eloquent impromptu speaker, he was always drawn to style; in his <em>Atlantic</em> essay, he invokes it in a higher form. “It is style,” he wrote, “which, in the domain of foreign policy, enables us to find a harmony between the pursuit of ends essential to us, and the regard for the views, the sensibilities, the aspirations of those to whom the problem may appear in another light.”<br><br> The problem Oppenheimer had in mind was arms control. He asked that those who negotiate on America&#39;s behalf carry out their work in a spirit of openness. He asked that they appeal to the reasoning minds of those who sit across the table. He appears to have believed—or to have wanted to believe—that a widespread adoption of this style might be enough to set into motion a new evolutionary step in geopolitics, through which the world&#39;s major powers might come to a shared understanding that peace is the highest wisdom. To this end, he counseled patience. Time and nature must be allowed to do their work, he noted. Seven decades on, it looks to be slow work indeed.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 17:41:20 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/j-robert-oppenheimer-ideas-history/674814/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/j-robert-oppenheimer-ideas-history/674814/</item></channel></rss>